<HEAD>Security Council Asked To Act For Iraqi Kurds</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Kurdish leader saying
fighting continues in Iraq. No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> said on Thursday that it has appealed to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> to `` act immediately to stop the massacre of Kurdish civilians by Iraqi forces.'' Meanwhile, the leader of the Kurdish rebels said that <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> government troops are still attacking guerrillas and civilians in northern <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> despite the government's amnesty offer. <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, the London-based human rights organization, said in a statement that it made its first direct appeal on Wednesday night to the 15-member <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> body in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> because the `` systematic and deliberate'' killings `` call out for immediate action by the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>.'' The statement charged <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> wants to punish the Kurds for their political sympathies and in retaliation for opposition Kurdish activities. More than 100,000 Iraqi Kurds fled across the border to <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> and many of them gave consistent accounts of the use of chemical weapons, the statement said. Amnesty last week accused <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> of killing hundreds of Kurdish villagers with chemical weapons in mountainous northern <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and of employing helicopter gunships, tanks and artillery in <LOCATION> Duhok </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mosul </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Arbil </LOCATION> provinces. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s ambassador to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadiq </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Mashat </PERSON>, denied chemical weapons were used. He was summoned to the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> on Tuesday and was told of British concern over the large numbers of Kurdish refugees and the reports of chemical weapons use. The latest <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> statement gave a qualified welcome to the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> amnesty for Kurds, saying it received reports in the past of Kurds being imprisoned and executed after responding to previous amnesties. <PERSON> Massoud </PERSON> <PERSON> Barzani </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Kurdistan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said in a telex sent to The Associated Press office in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> on Wednesday that the Kurds will not accept the general amnesty offered by <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> the day before. `` The Kurds have not struggled to be pardoned but to acheive their national and democratic rights within autonomy,'' <PERSON> Barzani </PERSON> said. `` Our struggle will continue until these goals are fulfilled.'' <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> launched the offensive against the Kurdish rebels after a cease-fire in its eight-year war with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> went into effect Aug. 20. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s 3.5 million Kurds have been struggling on and off for 50 years for an autonomous homeland. The <ORGANIZATION> Kurdistan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has said that nearly 2,000 civilians have been killed and another 5,000 injured, many by chemical weapons. In his statement Wednesday, <PERSON> Barzani </PERSON> said the amnesty offer was an attempt by <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> to deflect attention from its use of chemical weapons.
