<FIRST>r a PM-FairyShrimp     09-08 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fairy Shrimp,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Calif. County Moves To Save Fairy Shrimp's Skunk Hollow Swimming
Hole</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MURRIETA HOT SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tiny Riverside fairy shrimps can keep splashing around in their swimming hole thanks to county supervisors who ordered developers to help save the recently discovered fresh-water crustacean. Developers planned to bulldoze a low-lying pond and build more than 2,500 homes, unaware that the species, whose ancestors date back millions of years, occupied the seasonal pool. <LOCATION> Riverside </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> supervisors on Tuesday ordered <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tolman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Irvine </LOCATION> to preserve the threatened habitat after they were alerted by biologists who discovered the fairy shrimp species two years ago. The 22-legged fairy shrimp is about as wide as a pencil and 1 -LCB- inches long. It has been described by biologists as the most primitive crustacean living in fresh water. A group of biologists named the species the Riverside fairy shrimp after finding them in 15-acre Skunk Hollow pond and five smaller ponds in southern <LOCATION> Riverside </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, about 80 miles southeast of downtown <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. The fairy shrimp population survives dry summer months by burying eggs in the clay soil of the seasonal pools. The eggs of some desert species have been known to survive for as long as 25 years between adequate rains. The Board of Supervisors gave the developer and the biologists until Sept. 27 to come up with a proposal that would permit the survival of the fairy shrimp and <PERSON> Tolman </PERSON>'s proposed 2,571-unit housing project.
</TEXT>
