<HEAD>Neighbors Remember Slain IRA Man As `Friendly Lad'</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIXMILECROSS, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The elderly manager of a hardware store in this farming village remembered <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mullin </PERSON> as `` a friendly lad,'' a bricklayer who often dropped by for supplies. `` He just got caught up in the troubles because he knew nothing else,'' the manager said. `` He's only one of hundreds of young men in the area who have been harassed every day by the security forces.'' <PERSON> Mullin </PERSON>, 25, and two other local <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> men died in a British army ambush Aug. 30 as they drove along a country road near <LOCATION> Drumnakilly </LOCATION>, 5 miles north of here. Their funerals over the weekend drew mourners from all around the area and hundreds of riot police. The mourners, mostly Catholic, and the police, mostly Protestant, faced each other in stony silence. Physically, they were inches apart. Mentally, a gulf separated them. Police said the three dead men were armed and dressed in ski masks when they died. The <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> newspapers called them terrorists, murderers and `` IRA rats.'' But in the countryside of <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tyrone </LOCATION>, many residents knew these part-time guerrillas or their families and spoke of them in sympathetic terms. Their deaths helped exacerbate the divisions between local Catholics and the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION>'s most frequent targets in rural districts _ the police and the <ORGANIZATION> Ulster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regiment </ORGANIZATION>. `` There's a majority of Protestants with nothing wrong with them,'' said a 28-year-old decorator sitting on a grassy bank outside <ORGANIZATION> Dunmoyle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> on Saturday waiting for <PERSON> Mullin </PERSON>'s hearse to pass `` It's those that join the security forces we ca n't live with,'' he said, glancing at policemen searching mourners at a crossroads at the start of a two-mile trek to <PERSON> Mullin </PERSON>'s family farm outside <PERSON> Sixmilecross </PERSON>. Like the store manager, he spoke on condition of anonymity, fearing retaliation for criticizing the police. `` If you come up this road at 2 or 3 in the morning, and you're stopped by them, you're sure to get a kicking because of who you are,'' he said `` The police force would be welcome, surely, if they were 50-50 -LRB- Catholic-Protestant -RRB- and they were fair.'' The police and army say they ca n't get <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> recruits because the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> would kill them as collaborators. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallagher </PERSON>, 53, of <LOCATION> Strabane </LOCATION> in neighboring <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fermanagh </LOCATION>, said he was a `` political activist'' with two sons serving lengthy prison sentences for <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> bombings. `` The British never listen to anything except a gun,'' he said. `` You could n't name three countries the British have not been at war with.'' The mainly <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> is fighting to end British rule in predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> and unite it with the 95 percent <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>. Like many <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> recruits in rural districts alongside the <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>'s border, the slain men led double lives, their <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> activities camouflaged by ordinary civilian pursuits. <PERSON> Brothers </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON> and <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Harte </PERSON>, who were buried Friday in their nearby home village of <LOCATION> Loughmacrory </LOCATION>, were leading players in the local Gaelic football team. <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON> <PERSON> Harte </PERSON>, a 29-year-old architect, designed his own grandiose house overlooking the village. His 21-year-old brother was a carpenter. Both were married, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Harte </PERSON> to <PERSON> Mullin </PERSON>'s sister, and each had an infant son Police said <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON> <PERSON> Harte </PERSON> was the commander of the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION>'s mid-Tyrone unit and that his brother was responsible for selecting <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> targets from police and <ORGANIZATION> Ulster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regiment </ORGANIZATION> ranks <PERSON> Mullin </PERSON>, whose elder brother <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> is serving a life sentence for the 1977 <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> murder of a bus driver, was questioned after a bomb killed eight British soldiers Aug. 20 in a bus in nearby <LOCATION> Ballygawley </LOCATION>. He was released without charge after five days. News reports said the trio were on their way to kill an off-duty member of the <ORGANIZATION> Ulster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regiment </ORGANIZATION> when soldiers ambushed their stolen car. The government says the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> men fired first. At <PERSON> Mullin </PERSON>'s funeral, riot squads massed to block any repetition of the <ORGANIZATION> IRA </ORGANIZATION> gun salutes that have sparked clashes with police at previous burials. The 2,000 mourners inched along narrow country lanes, flanked by long lines of police in helmets, guns and riot shields. They trudged through rain-sodden fields, climbing over ditches and hedges and scattering cows and sheep. When one policeman fell over a barbed-wire fence, the crowd roared approval. Police ringed the church walls during the Mass, sometimes banging batons against shields in what sounded like a tribal beat. Three officers videotaped the crowd, and a helicopter clattered overhead, almost drowning out the graveside prayers. When the service ended, the crowd quickly dispersed. The weather switched from driving rain to warm sunshine, and the tensions from the 3 -LCB- - hour service lifted
