<SECOND>PM-North Korea-40 Years, Bjt,0907</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Korea Marks 40th Anniversary In Troubled Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four decades after its founding, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> remains an isolated, secretive state with an enigmatic leader who shows no signs of handing over power to his designated heir _ his son. The Democratic People's Republic of <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> celebrates its 40th anniversary Friday with praise for President <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON> <PERSON> Sung </PERSON>, 76, the communist strongman. The country plans a huge celebration, with senior foreign emissaries including President <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> <PERSON> Shangkun </PERSON> of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and Soviet <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> Chebrikov </PERSON> representing <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s two major allies. No political figures or journalists from the West have been invited, and requests from Western news agencies to cover the anniversary have gone unanswered. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> rarely allows <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> journalists into the country. The ceremonies Friday will include a mass rally, a sports competition and cultural performances in praise of <PERSON> Kim </PERSON>. `` Koreans respect <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON> <PERSON> Sung </PERSON> as a prominent leader in anti-Japanese warfare and hero of the Korean revolution,'' said <PERSON> Choe </PERSON> <PERSON> Kwan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ick </PERSON>, an official of the pro-North <ORGANIZATION> Korean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Korean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Residents </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Chongryon </LOCATION> -RRB-. `` He goes to every corner of the country, among farmers and workers, to solve problems they face. The people respect this, and that is why he has remained in power so long.'' A 1986 <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report called <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> `` the object of an intensive and far-reaching personality cult, probably unequalled in the rest of today's world.'' Huge statues of the Great Leader, as <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> is known, stand throughout the country and almost all <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Koreans </LOCATION> wear badges with his picture. Similar public loyalty to <PERSON> Kim </PERSON>'s son <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Jong </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON>, 46, is encouraged. The elder <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> plans to hand power over to his son in what may be the world's first communist dynasty. It has been a troubling year for <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. World attention has focused on rival <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and on the upcoming Olympic Games, which begin in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> Sept. 17. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has stressed security preparations against a possible terrorist attack from the north. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> finally stated this week that it would not use military or other means to interrupt the Olympics. `` As for ` terrorism,' it is utterly alien to us and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> itself is the chieftain of state terrorism as already exposed to the world,'' the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Korean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said. Tension remains high along the Demilitarized Zone with <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s deployment of Soviet-made missiles and jet fighters, including MiG-23s and MiG-29s. The North has an estimated 850,000 troops _ the world's fifth largest army _ against 650,000 <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> and 42,000 American soldiers. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> failed in its attempt to share in the glory of the Olympics, and is now watching allies <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and probably <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> establish trade relations with <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. Eclipsed by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> in industry and foreign trade, the country faces two formidable tasks: ensuring a smooth transfer of power and modernizing its economy. The country has a foreign debt of about $ 4.2 billion against foreign trade of only $ 3.5 billion annually, according to Western estimates. Last year, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> was declared in default on its foreign loans. Trade is modest, amounting to only $ 1.7 billion annually with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s largest trading partner and main economic benefactor. `` They -LRB- <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> -RRB- import machinery and vehicles, but lack parts and skill and ca n't get them repaired,'' a Japanese intelligence official said. To earn badly needed foreign currency, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> is on a building spree of luxury hotels and sports and cultural facilities, but `` they're building everything literally by hand, with shovels and wheelbarrows,'' the official said. `` It reminds me of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in the 1950s,'' said <PERSON> Masaru </PERSON> <PERSON> Nishida </PERSON>, a literature professor at <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Hosei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> who has visited the country three times. Strapped for cash, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has been shifting some of the 20 percent of its GNP currently spent on the military to joint ventures with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, according to the Japanese official. The products include household goods, clothing, shoes and are sold in <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION>. `` <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> wants to cut down military expenditures because they're a waste of money,'' said <PERSON> Choe </PERSON>. Authorities have demobilized 200,000 soldiers in the last two years and shifted them to economic reconstruction, he said. How to solidify the political position of <PERSON> Kim </PERSON>'s son is a more delicate issue. Little is known about <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Jong </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON>, but he clearly lacks the charisma of his father, the Japanese official said. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Pyong </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON>, 34, <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Jong </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON>'s half-brother, has been posted as ambassador to <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> in an apparent move to avoid a challenge to <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Jong </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON>, the official said. A major question is when <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON> <PERSON> Sung </PERSON> will abdicate in favor of his son _ or be forced to for health reasons. During a visit to <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION> in July, he had difficulty climbing slopes and once abandoned an attempt to enter a pavillion because he could not negotiate the stairs, the Japanese official said. `` <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON> <PERSON> Sung </PERSON> wants quickly to give reins to his son,'' the official said. `` But the domestic situation does n't allow that right now.'' He said <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> had been pressuring <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> not to put his son in power yet because they do not have complete confidence in him.
