<SECOND>PM-Jones Club,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Barnaby Jones' Club Thrives, To Delight Of Buddy Ebsen</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Do n't try to tell <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Camerada </PERSON> about <PERSON> Madonna </PERSON>, <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Selleck </PERSON> or <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON>. He's got his own idol: <PERSON> Barnaby </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>. `` I just like his easygoing style,'' <PERSON> Camerada </PERSON> says. Camerada is not alone. He is one of more than 800 members of the <PERSON> Barnaby </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> <PERSON> Fan </PERSON> <PERSON> Club </PERSON>, dedicated to the memory of the venerable detective who ambled across the nation's television screens from 1973 to 1980, and in countless reruns. Unlike most fan clubs, the members of this one actually get to meet their idol regularly. <PERSON> Buddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ebsen </PERSON>, who played <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, is a frequent guest at the club's weekly meetings at a restaurant off Times Square. `` It's a cult now,'' says <PERSON> Ebsen </PERSON>, 80. `` I love them. They're great guys. The great guys are mostly retired executives, men of <PERSON> Ebsen </PERSON>'s own generation. They include former President <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>, a fan of the show who joined the club at <LOCATION> Ebsen </LOCATION>'s suggestion. This fan club collects no dues, sells nothing, follows no rules and only loosely organizes an occasional golf outing. `` It is instantaneous. You walk in and you're a member,'' said member <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Desimone </PERSON>, 57. `` It really was a sincere, grass-roots germination,'' <PERSON> Ebsen </PERSON> said. President <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Lamberti </PERSON> said the club started some years ago when a retired <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> colonel was hospitalized for an operation. Each day, the patient watched <PERSON> Barnaby </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> reruns, and soon he and his visitors were hooked. Thereafter, they met for lunch or drinks each week. They would send <PERSON> Ebsen </PERSON> birthday cards each year. His curiosity was piqued, and one day he dropped in to La Vert-Galant, official meeting place of the <ORGANIZATION> BJFC </ORGANIZATION>. Now, whenever he's in town, <LOCATION> Ebsen </LOCATION> is a regular. And when he shows up, the bartender whips up an alcoholic drink that looks like the favored drink of the club's favorite detective _ a glass of milk. The meetings are not like Trekkie conventions _ there are no trivia contests, with questions of what color tie <PERSON> Barnaby </PERSON> wore in episode 33; there is no swap meet of <PERSON> Barnaby </PERSON> memorabilia. Mostly, the guys talk about sex, fights, baseball and dirty jokes. `` It's like a family,'' said <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON>, 60. The club has attracted Ebsen lookalikes and a Scottish man who, like <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, drank only milk. There are members in <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. Then there was the visit from <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ebsen </PERSON>, who is on the board of directors of <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s library, said he recruited <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> into the club when <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> asked him why the <PERSON> Barnaby </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> private detective show was taken off the air in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and how he could help get it back on. Now, said <PERSON> Ebsen </PERSON>, `` He's a card-carrying member.'' When <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> stopped by, more than 40 members gathered at the restaurant and listened to plenty of behind-the-scenes stuff, as <PERSON> Lamberti </PERSON> recalls. `` He was going to stay a half hour but he stayed two hours,'' he said. `` He told us things about <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> that I ca n't tell you. He said of all the clubs he ever went to this was the greatest because there was no ulterior motive.'' <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> also figured in another big moment in club history _ the time members rented a yacht and followed <PERSON> Ebsen </PERSON> in a race around <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. `` I had a <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> mask on,'' <PERSON> Lamberti </PERSON> said, with a chuckle. <PERSON> Ebsen </PERSON> said he recalls racing in the Liberty Regatta. There, tagging along behind him, was a yacht bearing a large banner. `` Go Barnaby,'' the sign said.
