<HEAD>Ninety-Seven Candidates For Nobel Peace Prize</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Norwegian <ORGANIZATION> Nobel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> says it will choose this year's Nobel Peace Prize laureate from 97 candidates, including 74 people and 23 organizations. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> reportedly are in the running for their agreement to dismantle intermediate range nuclear missiles. <PERSON> Jakob </PERSON> <PERSON> Sverdrup </PERSON>, secretary of the five-member committee, said Wednesday that the winner will be announced Sept. 29 by chairman <PERSON> Egil </PERSON> <PERSON> Aarvik </PERSON>. The number of approved candidates is close to the all-time record of 100. Last year, President <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> was chosen from among 93 candidates for his Central American peace plan. The committee refuses to confirm the names of candidates. Nominations for the 1988 prize closed on Feb. 1 Speculation has focused on <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>' General Secretary <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON>, who reportedly was nominated for the 1989 prize by Foreign Minister <PERSON> Hans-Dietrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> for his efforts to end the Iran-Iraq and <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> wars. A Norwegian member of parliament has said he has proposed President <PERSON> Cory </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> for her efforts for a peaceful tranisition in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. Prime Minister <PERSON> Gro </PERSON> <PERSON> Harlem </PERSON> <PERSON> Brundtland </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> reportedly was nominated for her U.N.-appointed work on drafting a program for environment and development. Other unconfirmed nominations were jailed black anti-apartheid leader <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, and Indian Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>. Members of <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>'s parliament reportedly have nominated the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- WHO -RRB- celebrating its 40th anniversary this year, and Swedish parliamentarians proposed the Rev. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Ingle </PERSON> of the Nashville-based <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jails </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prisons </ORGANIZATION>, who campaigns against the death penalty. This prize is worth about $ 385,000, up 15 percent from last year.
