<HEAD>Case Made of Murderer's Skin Sold At Auction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KNOWLE, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A visiting-card case made from the skin of executed 19th century mass murderer <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> was bought at auction for $ 1,785 by a man whose business takes tourists to the scenes of notorious crimes. `` The price was much more than <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hare </PERSON>, his accomplice, received for all the bodies of their victims, which they sold to anatomists,'' said <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, who bought the relic in a sale at <LOCATION> Knowle </LOCATION> in central <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hare </PERSON>, who began as grave-robbers, went on to murder at least 15 people in <LOCATION> Edinburgh </LOCATION> in 1827 and 1828, a time when medical professors could not get enough bodies for demonstrations to their students. <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> was hanged in 1829 on the evidence of <LOCATION> Hare </LOCATION>, who fled the city and disappeared. <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>'s body was flayed after dissection by <LOCATION> Edinburgh </LOCATION>'s medical authorities and part of his skin was used by one of those surgeons to make the ornate case with gold tooling which passed to his descendant _ who sold it Wednesday. A notebook covered in <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>'s skin is still in the possession of <LOCATION> Edinburgh </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Surgeons </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> is a partner in an <LOCATION> Edinburgh </LOCATION> guide business, which takes tourists to the scenes of notorious crimes. `` We will be showing the case to our clients on the tours,'' he said.
