</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> says the two sellers of chlordimeform, a pesticide used on an eighth of the nation's cotton crop which causes cancer in lab animals, are giving up their federal licenses for the product and will recall leftovers from farmers. The agency said Wednesday it would make the distribution or use of the chemical, used to destroy the eggs and larvae of the tobacco budworm and the cotton bollworm, illegal after Feb. 19. Pesticide recalls are rare, and a spokesman for one of the companies, <ORGANIZATION> Ciba-Geigy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said in <LOCATION> Greensboro </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, he could recall none that took products back from farmers. Recalls will begin in four or five weeks, after use for the current growing season is over, said the spokesman, <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>. Farmers will receive refunds for unused amounts and reimbursement for any shipping expenses. `` It's our hope'' that little will be left over, he said. The other license holder is Nor-Am <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Wilmington </LOCATION>, Del. <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> said he did not know whether Nor-Am bought its product from <ORGANIZATION> Ciba-Geigy </ORGANIZATION> or manufactured its own. At Nor-Am, spokesmen who could discuss chlordimeform were not immediately available. <ORGANIZATION> Ciba-Geigy </ORGANIZATION> has sold chlordimeform under the trade name Galecron, while Nor-Am sold it under the name <PERSON> Fundal </PERSON>. About a million pounds annually had been used in recent years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Private exporters have sold the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> an additional 300,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn for delivery during the coming year, says the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. More than 2 million tons of corn have been sold in the last week, according to <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> announcements. All have been for delivery in the 1988-89 which began on Sept. 1. A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 300,000 tons of corn would be about 11.8 million bushels. Corn prices have been averaging about $ 2.72 per bushel at the farm level, according to <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> estimates, meaning that the latest sale, announced Wednesday, could have a farm value of around $ 32 million. As with the other recent sales, no indication was given whether the new sales of corn would count under the current long-term grain supply agreement between the two countries or be carried forward separately in case a new pact is forthcoming. The current five-year pact is set to expire Sept. 30 and negotiators are trying to work out a new one, or at least an extension of the current agreement, to take effect Oct. 1.
