<FIRST>r a PM-Inheritance     09-08 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Inheritance,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bacteria Found To Pass On Acquired Characteristics To Offspring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bacteria can pass on to their offspring characteristics they acquire during their lifetimes, according to a discovery that challenges one of the central tenets of <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Darwin </PERSON>'s theory of evolution. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Cairns </PERSON> and colleagues at the <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> reported today that bacteria threatened with starvation can size up their troubles and mutate in ways that enable them to survive. <PERSON> Cairns </PERSON> said in a telephone interview that the inheritance of acquired characteristics can probably occur in other single-celled organisms like algae and fungi but is unlikely to occur in higher animals. <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Stahl </PERSON>, a professor of molecular genetics at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> in <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON>, said of <PERSON> Cairns </PERSON>' finding, `` It will be very interesting to a lot of biologists. Whether it's important _ it wo n't do anything to reduce the national debt.'' The idea that acquired characteristics could be passed on to succeeding generations was proposed early in the 19th century by <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Lamarck </PERSON>. But Lamarckism, as the theory was called, was generally discarded early in this century, said <PERSON> Stahl </PERSON>. If Lamarckism is correct, it would mean that a blacksmith, for example, who developed strong muscles during his lifetime, would be destined to have children with stronger-than-average muscles, said <PERSON> Cairns </PERSON>. The idea fell out of favor, <PERSON> Cairns </PERSON> said, because biologists could never explain how changes in muscles could lead to changes in sperm and eggs _ which would be necessary if the blacksmith's acquired characteristics were to be passed on to his children <PERSON> Cairns </PERSON> and his colleagues, <PERSON> Julie </PERSON> <PERSON> Overbaugh </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stephan </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, report their findings in Nature magazine. In an accompanying article, <PERSON> Stahl </PERSON> said the job of biologists now is to explain how bacteria can do this. Natural selection, <PERSON> Darwin </PERSON>'s theory that stands in opposition to Lamarckism, says that mutations arise spontaneously in organisms, and by chance some of those mutations may allow an organism to survive better than others of its kind. <PERSON> Cairns </PERSON> showed that the life-saving mutations in the bacteria he studied were produced in response to the stressful situation _ they were not naturally occurring variations that simply turned out to be advantageous.
</TEXT>
