<FIRST>r w PM-NuclearAccidents     09-08 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Accidents,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Ratifies Nuke Accident Treaties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Senate has voted unanimously to ratify two international conventions that were prompted largely by the <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> nuclear plant disaster in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The accords, approved by a 97-0 vote Wednesday, were negotiated under auspices of the Vienna-based <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atomic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. In the wake of the April 1986 <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> accident, <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> came under heavy criticism for delaying release of information on the reactor explosion to the outside world until large amounts of airborne radioactivity were detected in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>. Representatives of more than 60 countries met in the summer of 1986 to negotiate the two pacts: the Convention on Early Notification of a Nuclear Accident and the Convention on Assistance in the Case of a Nuclear Accident or Radiological Emergency. The notification convention has been signed by 72 countries, while the assistance convention has 70 signatories. In urging ratification, Sen. <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON> <PERSON> Pell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-R.I. </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, called the two conventions `` positive international achievements'' that could prove invaluable in case of another Chernobyl-scale nuclear accident. Under the early notification convention, each signatory nation pledges prompt notification of other affected countries and the atomic energy agency in case of a nuclear accident that is likely to result in the spread of radioactivity beyond its borders. Information to be provided includes: _ The time, exact location and nature of the accident _ The nuclear facility or activity involved _ The assumed or established cause and foreseeable further development of the accident _ Characteristics of the radioactivity released by the accident _ Weather conditions _ Environmental monitoring and protective measures taken or planned in the vicinity of the accident The second convention establishes an international legal framework for assistance by other nations in case it is requested by the government of a country hit by a major nuclear accident. It seeks to encourage such help, while not obligating any nation to provide assistance.
</TEXT>
