<FIRST>r i PM-Panama     09-08 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Noriega, President Take Pay Cut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALINA GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Cabinet voted to cut the pay of Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> and other top officials because of a cash shortage caused in part by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic sanctions. A Cabinet resolution passed Tuesday mandates pay cuts of 12.5 percent to 30 percent for <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, President <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Solis </PERSON> <PERSON> Palma </PERSON> and heads of state-owned companies. The government did not provide the individuals' salaries, but it said they make more than $ 3,000 a month. Salaries will return to normal `` when public finances allow,'' a government communique said. It acknowledged a `` deterioration'' in state income and said the pay cuts will save the government $ 230,000 a month. Business sources say the size of the economy is about half what it was in early 1987, before the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> imposed economic sanctions in an attempt to drive <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> from power. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, commander of the Defense Forces and the real power behind the civilian government, is reputed to have become independently wealthy during his military career. He is under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> indictment on drug trafficking charges. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> denies the drug trafficking charges and says the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is trying to undermine the Panamanian government as part of a plan to renege on the 1977 <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION> treaties. Under the treaties, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> must cede control of the canal at the turn of the century. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on Wednesday marked the 11th anniversary of the treaties, saying it would respect the accords but that relations with <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> could improve only with a democratic government in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. `` Panamanians and North Americans have worked together to implement the treaties and to ensure the continued and efficient operation of the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>. We promise that this will continue,'' the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement. It said, however, that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government `` continues believing that relations between our two peoples will be stronger when democracy is restored in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>.''
