ins placed in a casket for transfer to <LOCATION> Drumcliffe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sligo </LOCATION>, where he had asked to be buried, <PERSON> Yeats </PERSON> was quoted as saying. The <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Yeats </PERSON> as saying his mother oversaw the whole operation to transfer the bones and that he had documents from various officials who witnessed the procedure. Ms. <PERSON> Souhami </PERSON> said she never sought the kind of publicity to which <PERSON> Yeats </PERSON> referred, and `` offending people certainly was n't my intention.'' `` I'm sure he -LRB- <PERSON> Yeats </PERSON> -RRB- believes that story, but unfortunately the letters among <PERSON> Gluck </PERSON>'s papers do n't confirm his account,'' she told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. `` Unfortunately I have the letters from the priest in <LOCATION> Roquebrun </LOCATION> and letters from the undertakers.'' She said <PERSON> Hannah </PERSON> <PERSON> Gluck </PERSON> spent years trying to convince <PERSON> Yeats </PERSON>' friends the wrong bones went to <PERSON> Drumcliffe </PERSON> and that the affair needed to go into the biography because it illustrated her obsessive character
