<FIRST>r a PM-InsiderTrading-Milken     09-08 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Insider Trading-Milken,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Michael Milken Architect of `Junk Bond' Financing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Insider Training-Drexel, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>, who was charged by a federal lawsuit with insider trading, almost single-handedly built `` junk-bond'' financing into the tool of choice for corporate raiders during the past dozen years. <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> was seen for years as a Wall Street whiz kid, who had helped transform <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> from a minor player into a powerhouse. Even when it became known several months ago that he was under investigation for insider trading, <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> took the offensive. <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> waged a public-relations blitz, stressing the role of junk bonds _ notes that are highly risky but offer high yields _ in helping small companies get off the ground and downplaying their role megabuck takeover battles. The normally secretive <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>, 42, began accepting speaking engagements and granting some interviews _ with the condition that questions about the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and the investigation of him were off limits. His comments focused almost solely on his latest pet plan _ to alleviate the <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> debt crisis by swapping debt for equity or selling securities backed by those countries' oil and silver resources. <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> reportedly makes $ 40 million a year as the head of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s junk-bond operation. That is several times more than the firm's chairman. <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>'s personal fortune has been estimated at more than $ 500 million. He lives with his children and wife, <PERSON> Lori </PERSON> _ his high school sweetheart whom he married at age 22 _ in a house on the former estate of the late actor <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> <PERSON> Gable </PERSON> in suburban <LOCATION> Encino </LOCATION>, an upper-middle-class section of the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fernando </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> two miles from his childhood home. <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>'s fascination with finance dates to his boyhood. At age 10, a favorite pastime was poring over tax returns prepared by his father, an accountant. After studying business at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>, and the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Wharton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> went to work for <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Firestone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> as a junior bond trader. <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> merged with <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in 1973 and <PERSON> Lambert </PERSON> <PERSON> Brussels </PERSON> <PERSON> Witter </PERSON> in 1976, and <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>'s job was moved to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> worked hard to make a name for himself but never became acclimated to the East. In 1977, he persuaded <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> to let him move the company's junk-bond operations from <LOCATION> Wall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, just off swank Rodeo Drive <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> became enormously successful in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, building a close-knit network of junk-bond investors. He is in charge of the 150 people who work at <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>'s junk-bond operation. He still works 12 to 13 hours a day, seven days a week and wo n't tolerate lack of drive among those who work for him Associates say they need to make appointments to meet with him even on weekends. He once said he had no hobbies `` because what I do is fun.''
