<HEAD>Pope John Paul II Skips Dominant Country in Southern Africa Tour</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At the advice of the nation's bishops, Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> will bypass <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> _ the most populous and dominant country in southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> _ when he begins a visit to the region Saturday South African Catholics have written to newspapers and their church, expressing anger and disappointment that the pope is not stopping in their land. He will visit <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lesotho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Botswana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Swaziland </LOCATION>, all of which border <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Some <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> Catholics said they would withhold donations that would be used to finance the pope's visit to the poorer, neighboring countries. Others suggested the pope could have done some good by bringing a message of peace, reconciliation and respect for human rights to racially divided <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. The dispute is part of a growing tension between the South African government and church leaders who actively oppose apartheid, under which the nation's black majority has no voice in national affairs. No one in the church has said that the itinerary for the Sept. 10-19 visit is a snub of the South African government or a demonstration of the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>'s disapproval of apartheid. But the <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> government said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> was protesting apartheid by not going to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. It banned South African-based foreign journalists from covering the pope in <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Pik </PERSON> <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s office issued a statement Aug. 4 saying the bishops were to blame for the pope skipping <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> because they had not invited him, although they had been told the government would welcome a visit. The Southern African <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bishops </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> said it invited the pope to come to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> in 1982 but has been unable to arrange a date. The conference said it would be impractical to squeeze a large country like <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> into a tour already covering five nations. `` There has been a lot of misunderstanding about the whole thing,'' said the archbishop of <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Naidoo </PERSON>. `` The pope never said he would n't come.'' He called <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s Aug. 4 statement `` mischievous.'' The <PERSON> pope </PERSON> said in July that he would like to visit <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> some day but that the bishops told him it would not be appropriate at this time. He did not elaborate. South African security police this week went to the home of Anglican Archbishop <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> to collect a recording of his latest sermon. They were investigating whether he had violated emergency regulations by calling for a boycott of October municipal elections. Law and Order Minister <PERSON> Adriaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> said last week the government may `` clip the wings'' of activist clergymen who vowed to begin a civil disobedience campaign against emergency rules. The Rev. <PERSON> Smangaliso </PERSON> <PERSON> Mkhatshwa </PERSON>, secretary-general of the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bishops </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>, was released from detention last year after church officials filed court affidavits in which he swore he was being tortured. He was subsequently charged with possession of a gun, which he denies. The schedule for the pope's 10-day visit includes beatification of a French missionary in <LOCATION> Lesotho </LOCATION>, a bishops' conference in <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>, and outdoor Masses in <LOCATION> Botswana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Swaziland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>. The pope received South African President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> at the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> in 1984 and there are plans for him to send greetings during one of his two flights over the country, on his way to <LOCATION> Lesotho </LOCATION> and to <LOCATION> Swaziland </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Lesotho </LOCATION> is surrounded by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Swaziland </LOCATION> is bordered on three sides by its huge neighbor. Hundreds of thousands of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africans </LOCATION>, black and white, are expected to cross the border to see the pope. Many thousands are also expected in <LOCATION> Botswana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>. Just as <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> dominates communications, trade, transportation and politics in the region, its influence will be felt strongly during the <PERSON> pope </PERSON>'s trip. South African firms are supplying transportation, food, water and health services, broadcasting and emergency equipment to be used on many of the pope's stops. Local coordinating committees are selling papal souvenirs through South African franchises, to defray the expenses of building podiums for the outdoor rallies, providing accommodations for dignitaries and pilgrims, and arranging for security and traffic control.
