<FIRST>r i PM-Bangladesh-Floods     09-08 0713</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bangladesh-Floods,0734</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rivers Receding But Miseries Remain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rivers across this flooded nation receded slightly today, but the change brought little relief to people still boating and wading through murky waters to get food and uncontaminated water. The death toll from the floods that started June 13 and subsided only to rise with new vengeance on Aug. 27 was 416 according to the government, whose count is generally considered low. The independent Bengali-language newspaper Khobar today reported 34 new drownings and snake-bite deaths, bringing the unofficial toll to 1,301. The Buriganga and Sitlakhya rivers that wrap around <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION> on three sides fell between 1 -LCB- to 4 inches in the last 24 hours but were still as much as 45 inches above flood level, the flood control center reported. About three-fourths of <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>, an impoverished low-lying nation of 110 million people, remained under water ranging from a few inches in some areas to at least 10 feet in others. In <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION>, a city of 6 million, streets were turned into canals clogged with boats ferrying people to work, to food markets and relief centers and to spigots to get drinking water. At least half the capital was still under water. In the <LOCATION> Shaymoli </LOCATION> neighborhood in northern <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION>, two young seamstresses waded waist deep in front of the four-story building that houses the small Fairy Fashion Factory where they work. `` Eleven of us are living in the factory because our homes are flooded,'' said 20-year-old <PERSON> Shamima </PERSON>, who uses only one name. `` There has been no electricity for two weeks, so we ca n't work and we do n't know if we'll be paid, but the owner is bringing us food.'' She and her friend, 17-year-old <PERSON> Lily </PERSON>, said they waded through the flood each day to buy about five gallons of drinking water for 31 cents. They said the water proably was n't pure, but it was all they could get. `` Most of us have fevers and headaches,'' <PERSON> Lily </PERSON> said. Both young women said they had heard about water purification tablets but were n't using any. `` No one has given us any, and we do n't have enough money to buy any,'' <PERSON> Lily </PERSON> said. The government says it is distributing water purification tablets throughout the country, but they are in short supply. A diplomat from a Western nation that has been trying to buy water tablets for relief distribution reported searching in vain for sufficient quantities in <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> and nearby countries. The diplomat spoke on condition of anonymity. Of more than two dozen people questioned at random in <LOCATION> Shaymoli </LOCATION>, only one man _ a pharmacy shopkeeper _ said he was using them. The government's health control center reported 16,813 new cases of diarrhea Wednesday, bringing the total of known cases across the country to 119,822 since Aug. 27. At least 83 of the afflicted people died, and their deaths were included in the government's toll of flood victims The government says at least 25 million people have lost their homes in the flooding. Relief camps have been set up in an effort to help people whose homes were washed away or are filled with flood water, but many other people have moved in with relatives, living on rooftops or camping in makeshift shelters on bits of high ground. <PERSON> Abul </PERSON> <PERSON> Hashem </PERSON>, a 50-year-old auto mechanic, has been living for the past two weeks on the roof of a corrugated tin shed in <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION>. He said he tried to find other shelter but relief centers where he went were full. He and nine other men and boys pitched tents on the roof of sheds facing their homes. `` I could n't leave my things,'' he said, pointing to his own tin house where the water reached nearly to the roof. `` There is nothing important there, but whatever I have is mine and I'm afraid of robbers.'' <PERSON> Abul </PERSON> <PERSON> Hashem </PERSON> and others in the neighborhood said robbers came at night in motorboats and looted abandoned houses and businesses. <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION> newspapers also have reported that robbers were operating from boats, but the government denied there had been an increase in break-ins. Home Minister <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Matin </PERSON> said the number of thefts had not increased, and the only difference was that thieves were now coming by boat instead of land.
</TEXT>
