<HEAD>With PM-Wildfires, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a summary of developments in forest and brush fires in Western states:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WYOMING:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Fire gutted 17 buildings at <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION>'s Old Faithful geyser complex Wednesday. About 200 firefighters protected other structures, including the historic Old Faithful Inn. Overnight visitors to Old Faithful were asked to leave Wednesday morning in the first-ever evacuation of the most popular tourist attraction at the 116-year-old park. The nearby 165,000-acre North Fork fire is one of 13 major blazes covering more than 1 million acres in and around <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>. East of <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Shoshone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> officials evacuated at least 50 ranches and summer homes in a sparsely populated area because of rapid growth of the 260,000-acre Clover Mist fire.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MONTANA:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Two men were reported missing west of <LOCATION> Glacier </LOCATION> <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> early today as flames raced near their remote home. The blaze, discovered Tuesday, expanded to an estimated 7,500 acres by early today and moved into the park. There it burned a ranger station complex and numerous cabins. Four hikers in the park were rescued by helicopter Wednesday after flames cut off their escape route. More than 100 people were evacuated because of the blaze, and two park campgrounds were evacuated and closed. Along Yellowstone's northern border, high winds drove a deliberately set backfire along the northern edge of <LOCATION> Cooke </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and nearby Silver Gate. The fire singed the fringes of the <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> towns but created a buffer zone of charred timber in advance of the 119,000-acre Storm Creek-Hellroaring fire. Elsewhere, winds sent wildfires boiling through timber in the <LOCATION> Bitterroot </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Range </LOCATION> near the <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> line, northeast of <PERSON> Ovando </PERSON> along the <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Divide </ORGANIZATION>, and in a wide area to the north and south of <LOCATION> Augusta </LOCATION> along the <ORGANIZATION> Rocky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>. Dozens of people were evacuated from homes in the paths of the blazes.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>IDAHO:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 A number of fires in the <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Church-River </PERSON> of No Return Wilderness reached nearly 60,000 acres. To the north, seven fires continued to burn out of control in the <LOCATION> Nez </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Perce </LOCATION> <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Forest </LOCATION>, covering nearly 89,000 acres.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Prime fruit orchards were spared from a raging forest fire in central <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state by farmers turning on their irrigation systems, by a shift in winds and by cooler weather. The dampened apple and pear orchards near the <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Entiat </LOCATION> helped keep the spreading 32,000-acre fire from all but one home, which was destroyed. About 700 firefighters used bulldozers in an attempt to ring the fire, while aircraft and helicopters bombed it with water and flame retardant. The fire is the largest of a half-dozen in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> that burned 65,000 acres.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>OREGON:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Firefighters declared the lightning-caused Teepee Butte fire in northeastern <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> under control after it burned nearly 60,000 acres of the <ORGANIZATION> Wallowa-Whitman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> and the Hell's <ORGANIZATION> Canyon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Recreation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Area </ORGANIZATION> over the past two weeks. It was the state's largest blaze.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CALIFORNIA:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Crews set a backfire north of Shelter Cove to protect the coastal tourist town from a stubborn blaze that swept out of control over 1,600 acres of the rugged King Mountain Range, about 225 miles north of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>UTAH:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Firefighters contained a 5,400-acre brush fire east of <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, but scrambled to battle seven new fires in the state, including one that destroyed a cabin and a barn north of White Rocks in eastern <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>COLORADO:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Five wildfires whipped by gusting winds spread rapidly Wednesday along <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>'s northeastern mountains and foothills, forcing evacuation of 25 homes north of Golden and an undetermined number of people from a <LOCATION> Boulder </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Boy Scout camp. There were no reports of property damage, and a total of about 4,800 acres were charred statewide.
