<SECOND>PM-Potato Scandal,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former State Official Pleads Guilty To Misdemeanor In Potato
Scandal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB IMRIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former state administrator escaped bribery charges by pleading guilty to a misdemeanor in connection with a failed attempt to sell potatoes to <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> that rocked state politics. `` It is time to put our lives back together,'' said <PERSON> Laurence </PERSON> <PERSON> McMerty </PERSON>, the state <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s former marketing director. `` It has been an awfully emotionally draining affair for my family.'' The state agreed to drop bribery charges against McMerty after he pleaded guilty Wednesday to unlawful compensation for assistance in a government matter. He faces up to one year in jail and a $ 1,000 fine. No date for sentencing was set. McMerty, 43, admitted taking $ 3,200 in cash from <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Messner </PERSON>, a Miami-based middleman in the botched 1986 deal involving the sale of 4 million pounds of potato seed to a <LOCATION> Honduran </LOCATION> cooperative. McMerty claimed the money was reimbursement for expenses. The former administrator had been accused of accepting a <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> cruise and up to $ 4,000 in cash from <PERSON> Messner </PERSON>, and jury selection for a bribery trial had started in state district court Wednesday morning before McMerty agreed to the misdemeanor plea. The bribery charges carried a maximum penalty of 10 years in prison. `` I am confident and comfortable justice has been served,'' Deputy Attorney General <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Quick </PERSON> said of the plea arrangement. The bribery charges were based almost entirely on circumstantial evidence, Quick said. Some evidence would have indicated McMerty was `` duped by <PERSON> Messner </PERSON>, at least partially,'' he said. `` I characterize this case as one of criminal bad judgment.'' The case is credited with ruining the political career of Agriculture Commissioner <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, a Republican who was denied endorsement for a third term because of the lingering scandal. The <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> deal collapsed after Attorney General <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Spaeth </PERSON> raised questions about its financing, and the state has never been paid $ 104,000 due for the only 400,000-pound potato shipment that was delivered. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> became embroiled in the controversy when he and the former president of the state-owned <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dakota </ORGANIZATION> signed a $ 300,000 note meant to help finance the deal. <PERSON> Messner </PERSON> later sold the note to a <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> bank for $ 264,000, putting $ 180,000 of the money in his personal bank account to cover overdrafts, the state has said. <PERSON> Messner </PERSON> pleaded guilty July 8 to bribery as part of a plea agreement that requires him to pay $ 60,888 in restitution to the state. <PERSON> Messner </PERSON>, who was placed on probation, was in jail for six months prior to the plea.
