<SECOND>PM-Encephalitis,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Shows Encephalitis Vaccine Is Effective</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A vaccine is highly effective against an epidemic form of encephalitis that is a major health problem among children in parts of <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, according to a report published today. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> study tested a vaccine used to control the Japanese encephalitis virus. Although its primary victims are school-age children, the virus also affects travelers and military personnel. Encephalitis vaccine has been administered to millions of children in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> since the 1960s, but the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> study was the first to test the effectiveness of the most widely used versions of the vaccine. At $ 2.30 per dose the vaccine is relatively expensive, and Japanese encephalitis is still a major health hazard in many parts of <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. The study was conducted on 65,224 children in northern <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, where the disease strikes 10 to 20 of every 100,000 people. This rate is similar to polio at its worst in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. According to a report in the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>, two-thirds of youngsters received two doses of vaccine, while the rest got dummy shots. The attack rate was 5 per 100,000 in those getting vaccine and 51 per 100,000 in the comparison group. The study directed by Dr. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoke </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Walter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> concludes that the vaccine is safe and effective. In an accompanying editorial, Dr. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Monath </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> noted that the vaccine is not available to Americans abroad because of its manufacturer's concerns about liability However, he said efforts are under way to resolve this issue, and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> is reviewing applications to sell the vaccine in this country.
