<FIRST>r a PM-WhoopingCough     09-08 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Whooping Cough,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Finds No Link Between Whooping Cough Vaccine and Crib Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Babies who are vaccinated against whooping cough face no unusual risk of crib death, as some experts had feared, according to a major study published today. The report was based on a review of 129,834 vaccinated babies. It found that the risk of crib death is actually lower than usual after the shots. Some research has suggested that babies have an increased risk of sudden infant death syndrome, or SIDS, immediately after receiving immunization for whopping cough, also known as pertussis. Babies are routinely given the so-called DTP vaccine, which protects them from diphtheria, tetanus and pertussis. The study by Dr. <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> <ORGANIZATION> Vanderbilt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> finds no support for this concern. `` We conclude in this large population of children there was no increase in the risk of SIDS after immunization with the DTP vaccine,'' they wrote in the New England Journal of Medicine. Doctors generally recommend that children receive five doses of the vaccine _ three during the first six months, one after the first birthday and one before starting school. Crib death is considered to be the sudden, unexpected death of an infant or young child when no specific cause of death can be found. It is most common before the first birthday, accounting for 30 percent of all deaths in the age group. The study was based on children born between 1974 and 1984 in four <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> counties. The researchers compared the risk of SIDS deaths during the first month after vaccination with the risk later in infancy. They found that that during the first week after vaccination, the risk was less than 20 percent that of later periods. `` The most plausible explanation for the decreased rate of SIDS in the period immediately after immunization is that children may be immunized when they are in better health and that this healthier state is associated with a lower risk of SIDS,'' they wrote.
</TEXT>
