<HEAD>Floods, Earthquakes, Storms and Heat Hit Asia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bangladesh Floods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a summary of natural disasters that have hit <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> since June: FLOODS: Aug. 27 _ Floods triggered by annual monsoons claim at least 416 lives in <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> and leave more than 21 million people homeless. Newspapers claim more than 1,200 people are killed. At one time, three-fourths of the impoverished nation is under water. Because wells and pumps are submerged, people begin drinking flood water, prompting a rise in diarrhea cases. EARTHQUAKES: Aug. 20 _ An earthquake registering 6.5 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale jolts the Himalayan mountains, foothills and plains of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>. It is the deadliest temblor in the region in 30 years. At least 714 people are killed in <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> and 281 in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. The official tolls are considered understated because the monsoons cut off roads to many remote villages. Tens of thousands of homes, mostly of brick and mud, are destroyed. Aug. 6 _ An earthquake measuring 7.3 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale shakes <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>, northern <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and parts of <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. Four people die in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. STORMS: Aug. 16 _ A storm kills 1,406 people and causes $ 1.2 billion in damage to the central Chinese province of <LOCATION> Shaanxi </LOCATION>. It also triggers mountain torrents that destroy 3,000 homes, 14,326 acres of farmland and washes away 165 miles of highway. Officials call it the most destructive storm in the country's history. Sept. 2 _ Landslides caused by torrential rains kill at least 35 people in various parts of <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>. HEAT: June 4 _ Northern and central <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> swelter in the worst heat in 20 years, with temperatures climbing as high as 117 degrees for nearly three weeks. The government says at least 450 people died, most in the desert state of <LOCATION> Rajasthan </LOCATION>.
