<HEAD>Cruise Missiles Leave Britain</HEAD>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Molesworth</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with missiles leaving Britain.
Pick up 4th graf pvs: `The small ...' EDITS to conform.
^By MAUREEN JOHNSON</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALCONBURY, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Showered with confetti by anti-nuclear campaigners, the first <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cruise missiles to leave <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> under the superpower arms control treaty were flown out of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> today, less than a year after they arrived. `` Good riddance, do n't come back!'' shouted the protesters outside the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> air base at <LOCATION> Molesworth </LOCATION>, 50 miles north of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, as two of the 18 cruise missiles, the most recent to be deployed in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, were driven away aboard camouflaged mobile launchers. The vehicles headed to the nearby base at <LOCATION> Alconbury </LOCATION>, where the missiles were put aboard a C141 aircraft and the launchers aboard a Galaxy C5. The two giant transport planes took off at 2 p.m. -LRB- 9 a.m. EDT -RRB- for a 12-hour non-stop flight, with midair refueling, to <ORGANIZATION> Davis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monthan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> for destruction under Soviet supervision. The small group of anti-nuclear campaigners watched the missiles on board two 55-foot transporters lumber through the gates and across the flat <LOCATION> Cambridgeshire </LOCATION> countryside for the last time. The protesters carried banners saying: `` This is only the first step.'' `` This is something we have been working for for nine years,'' said <PERSON> Meg </PERSON> <PERSON> Beresford </PERSON>, secretary of the Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament. At <LOCATION> Molesworth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION> Ambassador to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Price </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> hailed the missile departure as an achievement for the unity of the 16-nation <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> alli