<HEAD>South Korea Urged to Release Prisoners, Change Laws</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> is improving its human rights record but holds about 600 political prisoners, and torture still occurs, <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> said today. The international human rights group urged the <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> government to make further improvements. It called for the release of political prisoners, an end to torture and other ill-treatment of detainees and changes in laws to allow peaceful expression of opposition to the government. The report comes a week before the opening of the Olympic Games in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. In a report called `` Detention of Prisoners of Conscience and Torture Continue,'' <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> noted that major political changes since last summer have ushered in some improvements in the human rights area. The government of President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> Tae-woo came into power after <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>, then chairman of the ruling party, pledged a package of democratic reforms, including release of political prisoners, in response to violent demonstrations in June 1987. `` There have been releases and amnesties, but we think they've been too few,'' the group said While the government says nearly 1,300 political prisoners have been released since last year, <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> claims the number is 400. The human rights group also said 4,000 former political prisoners' civil rights have been restored in this period, about half the number claimed by the government. The report said `` arrests on political grounds have continued,'' with about 600 people imprisoned for political or trade union activities. Among the 600, <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> is calling for the release of 28 it has adopted as prisoners of conscience, and is