<HEAD>`Wizard of Oz' Cinematographer Dies At Age 93</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosson </PERSON>, a pioneering cinematographer whose work included `` The Wizard of Oz'' and who was married to screen legend <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Harlow </PERSON>, has died at age 93. <PERSON> Rosson </PERSON> died Tuesday at his home in <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Terry </PERSON>, a nephew. His first movie was the silent `` <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Harum </PERSON>'' in 1915. He went on to direct the photography for such movies as `` Gentlemen Prefer Blondes'' in 1928, `` Treasure Island'' in 1934, `` Duel in the Sun'' in 1947 and `` Singin' in the Rain'' in 1952. His last film was `` <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dorado </LOCATION>,'' in 1967. During his 52-year career, many of <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>'s top directors, including <PERSON> Cecil </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> DeMille </PERSON>, <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Dwan </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Howard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hawks </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Sternberg </PERSON> and <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Vidor </PERSON>, requested him for their films. He helped bring the elegant polish to <ORGANIZATION> Metro </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Goldwyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayer </PERSON> films of the 1930s and 1940s, including `` The Wizard of Oz'' in 1939. <PERSON> Rosson </PERSON>, a native of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, became Ms. <PERSON> Harlow </PERSON>'s third and last husband in 1933. After her death in 1937, he married <PERSON> Yvonne </PERSON> <PERSON> Crellin </PERSON>. They later divorced. He had no children. He shared an honorary Academy Award in 1936 with <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Greene </PERSON> for pioneering color cinematography on the desert melodrama `` The Garden of Al