<HEAD>Afghan Refugees To Be Trained In Mine Disposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Afghan refugees are to be trained to dispose of the thousands of land mines left by Soviet and government forces during the war in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> official said today. The proposed program by the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> office coordinating aid for <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> also calls for public information campaigns to warn women and children who return home about the danger of mines planted in Afghan fields and roads. `` The first step is to train one or two returnees per village to have some idea of how to defuse a mine and dispose of it,'' said the official, an aide to the chief of the Geneva-based office, Prince <PERSON> Sadruddin </PERSON> <PERSON> Aga </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON>. The official spoke on condition he not be identified by name. The number of mines littering the Afghan countryside is estimated at hundreds of thousands to several million, the aide said. Using posters and radio programs, the campaign would `` try to inform as many as possible on the hazards, so women and children would be able to recognize a mine and not, for example, pick it up,'' he said. Another aspect would be first aid training `` since there will unfortunately always be people blown up by mines,'' he added. Two basic types of mines were used in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>: traditional anti-tank devices placed on roads, mountain passes or around garrisons, and smaller anti-personnel mines designed to maim people. Millions of Afghans fled to neighboring countries such as <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Iran </ORGANIZATION> to escape the decade-long fighting between the Soviet-backed <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government and Moslem guerrillas seeking its overthrow. The Afghan government says 150,000 refugees have returned home since the signing of the U.N.-sponsored <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> accord last April, but the figure has not been independently confirmed. Soviet troops intervened in neighboring <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in December 1978 to help prop up a Marxist government. Under the <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> agreement, <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> pledged to withdraw half its contingent by last month and to complete the pullout by mid-February. U.N officials have said the Soviets already have pulled out more than half its troops.
