<HEAD>Cosmonauts Discuss Problem-Plagued Spaceflight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cosmonauts just returned from a problem-plagued space mission described cramped quarters, food and water shortages and equipment problems but did not address questions about their performance, a <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> dispatch indicated today. The government newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> had suggested Wednesday that the commander of the Soyuz TM-5 capsule, stranded in orbit for a day, may have worsened equipment problems by not following proper emergency procedures. The capsule, carrying commander <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyakhov </PERSON> and the first Afghan in space, <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahad </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohmand </PERSON>, landed safely early Wednesday in the Central Asian republic of <LOCATION> Kazakhstan </LOCATION>. At a news conference today for Soviet and Afghan reporters at the Baikonur Space Center, near the landing site, the cosmonauts said they had only 105 cubic feet between them. They were stuck in the capsule for 26 hours. `` Immobility was the biggest problem,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>, the official news agency, reported. The cosmonauts had an emergency supply of food and water, but decided not to use it until absolutely necessary, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. Other reports have said the capsule had no toilet, virtually no room to move around, and enough air for only two days. The spacemen were asked about problems that forced postponement of their reentry after their capsule undocked Tuesday from the orbiting space station Mir. `` During the first landing attempt, undertaken on Sept. 6, everything went as scheduled,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Lyakhov </PERSON> as saying. `` But 30 seconds before the engine start-up, there occurred a disruption in the operation of the infrared vertical sensor. The computer was unable to judge whether the spacecraft was correctly oriented, and the engine was shut off.'' The engine <PERSON> Lyakhov </PERSON> referred to is supposed to brake the capsule so it can safely pass through the atmosphere. The cosmonaut said a second attempt to fire the engine was made later, but that it slowed the capsule too much and the burn was terminated. Landing was put off until Wednesday. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> did not report any comments by the crew at the news conference about their performance. The newspaper said reporters asked deputy flight chief <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> Blagov </PERSON> whether the commander failed to follow proper procedure during the second landing attempt. <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Blagov </PERSON> as saying: `` We still must painstakingly study the whole situation.'' <PERSON> Blagov </PERSON> said backup landing sites could have been used, so there was no rush to fire the reentry engine. Then, appearing to defend <PERSON> Lyakhov </PERSON>, he said it `` could be understood in a purely human way'' why the commander wanted to land at the designated time and place. <PERSON> Lyakhov </PERSON> had said in a capsule-side interview broadcast on television Wednesday that he and <LOCATION> Mohmand </LOCATION> had wanted to make a third attempt at landing on Tuesday but that the craft might have touched down outside Soviet territory. He said the crew preferred to wait until landing could be assured in <LOCATION> Kazakhstan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lyakhov </PERSON>, a 47-year-old veteran military pilot, flew in space for 175 days in 1979 and 150 days in 1983. The public questioning of a cosmonaut's performance was highly unusual in the Soviet space program. It reflected the more open discussion of problems encouraged by Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> under his policy of `` glasnost.''
