<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The skipper of the <ORGANIZATION> USS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vincennes </ORGANIZATION> was warned that a plane approaching the ship July 3 might be a commercial airliner, but he ordered the ship's missiles fired in the mistaken belief it was an Iranian F-14, <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> investigators told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> today. The warning was called out by one of the officers in the confusion of the combat center on the <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION>, the investigators said. Capt. <PERSON> Will </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> waved his hand in acknowledgement of the warning. But other factors, most of them human errors by crew members made under stress, led <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> to erroneously conclude that the plane approaching his ship was an Iranian military jet that had just taken off from a military-civilian airfield at <PERSON> Bandar </PERSON> <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Iran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> Flight 655, which had flown out of the same airfield, was shot down by two missiles from the <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hormuz </LOCATION>, killing all 292 persons aboard. Rear Adm. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fogarty </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> investigating team, said his probe had turned up a number of mistakes by the <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> crew. Among those mistakes were erroneously concluding that the plane was descending rather than climbing, and that the plane was outside a civilian air corridor. <PERSON> Fogarty </PERSON> outlined to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> the report released by the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> three weeks ago. There was no criticism of <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION> among panel members. `` The easiest thing any of us can do is second-guess, and that's not what we want to do,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass The <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> is a $ 1 billion Aegis-class cruiser, equipped with the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s most sophisticated air defense system. <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> investigators attributed the incident to human errors made under stress and during `` the fog of war.'' They said <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officers misread data from the Aegis system and gave mistaken information to <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION>. A public version of the report was released three weeks ago. A classified version has also been sent to <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. Sen. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, D-Ga., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said many of the questions surrounding the incident had been answered by the Fogarty investigation `` But we want a chance to talk to him in person and ask some questions,'' <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> explained. `` I think we are going to be looking at how the Aegis system performed, how the weapons on board performed, and other secondary questions like that.'' The Fogarty investigation found that the Aegis system worked as designed. `` Overall, I think I'm pretty sympathetic to the plight of the captain and I think there's a lot of sympathy for him here, given the compressed time frame for making a decision and given the other constraints of operating a blue-water ship in a brown-water environment,'' <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> said. He was referring to using the <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION>, which was designed for large-scale, open-ocean situations, in the small, crowded <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION