<HEAD>Marches, Strike Cripple Rangoon, Foreigners Evacuated</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with mob beheadings and government
shootings, Japan evacuating some dependents. Deletes reference to
soldiers and police marching. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 1 million people, including government officials and intelligence agents, marched in the capital today demanding democracy. Mobs beheaded three people who tried to poison the protesters. In a <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> suburb, security forces shot and injured 17 people to halt looting. The capital came to a standstill as uniformed state factory workers, <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> monks and <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> nuns, housewives and a group of 200 blind people joined in mass marches and a general strike to demand an end to 26 years of authoritarian rule. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and other foreign governments evacuated dependents of diplomats and other citizens, diplomats said. An attempt by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to do the same was delayed by an airport strike. Residents said more than 700,000 protesters marched in <LOCATION> Mandalay </LOCATION>, 350 miles north of <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>, and the same number in <LOCATION> Monywa </LOCATION>, an important trading town 60 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Mandalay </LOCATION>. About 100,000 marched in <LOCATION> Moulmein </LOCATION>, the Mon State capital 50 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>. A Western diplomat in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> said the evacuations were ordered because embassies believed the country was `` sliding toward chaos.'' Factory workers, <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> monks, <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> nuns, students and teachers marched through the capital to press for an end of repressive, one-party rule. Opposition leaders are demanding an interim government to usher in a multiparty system. Also participating were employees of the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>, the Parliament office, the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Special </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigation </ORGANIZATION>, or civilian intelligence, and uniformed officers of the state-owned shipping line. Most held banners identifying their groups. The protest was the largest in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> since Aug. 24, when President <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> lifted martial law in the capital and nationwide curfews. Today's march was largely peaceful, but sources said a mob beat to death two men and a woman who gave poisoned ice water to several demonstrators, including schoolchildren, and then beheaded them. Demonstrators took the three to a monastery. After they confessed to having been paid $ 42 each to poison protesters, a waiting mob dragged them outside and beheaded them, hanging their heads on posts at a major junction. It was not clear whether any protesters had been poisoned. State-run <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rangoon </ORGANIZATION> said security forces today shot and wounded 17 people as authorities moved to stop a mob of 500 people from looting a cigarette factory in a <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> suburb. An army officer was overpowered by mobs and beaten near the capital's Swedagon Pagoda, it said The radio said authorities the previous day retrieved from <LOCATION> Inya </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> seven bodies of people who had been stabbed and drowned. Government radio had said Wednesday that security forces had shot dead five people and wounded six to halt widespread looting in the capital the past two days. It said looting had broken out in 38 areas of the capital and that more than $ 43 million in state property had been plundered since the beginning of August. The deaths brought to at least 117 the number of protesters reported killed by security forces since last month. Foreign diplomats say the death toll could be in the hundreds. Diplomatic sources said 37 dependents of <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Embassy </LOCATION> officials were evacuated Wednesday. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, with about 50 nationals, have the largest missions in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>. The sources said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> had recalled more than 100 technicians and others would be evacuated. Japanese authorities said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s largest aid donor, recently evacuated some dependents of embassy staff and has urged businessmen and dependents of Japanese nationals to leave <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>. Others embassies also were evacuating dependents. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> had planned to evacuate the first of its up to 100 dependents today, but their commercial flight to <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, was canceled due to a strike at <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. Opposition leaders hoped today's would be the largest of the many mass protests that have driven two governments from office in less than two months. Demonstrators have not threatened foreigners and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy has been a popular rallying point, with protesters applauding the American flag. Leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> Burma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> planned a meeting Monday to consider a referendum on one-party rule, despite a protesters' demand for an interim government first. The party has ruled since a 1962 military coup that brought Ne Win to power. His rigid socialist and isolationist policies have made <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> one of the world's poorest nations. Turmoil began in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> with student riots in September 1987 that led to street protests in March and June. Ne Win resigned July 23 and was succeeded by a hard-line former general, <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON>, who lasted only 17 days. He was replaced by <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s first civilian leader since 1962. <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> called for the referendum on ending one-party rule.
