<HEAD>Paper's Attorney Says JOA Should Be Allowed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge was urged today to allow <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s two daily newspapers to complete a partial merger under a joint operating agreement approved last month by then-Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>. Attorney <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON> dismissed suggestions by opponents of the joint operating agreement -LRB- JOA -RRB- that <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> had ignored the conclusions of an administrative law judge that the papers didn's qualify for the anti-trust exemption <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> `` is under no compunction at any stage of the proceeding to accept any conclusion of the administrative law judge,'' said <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON>, who represents <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, owner of the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. Before leaving office last month, <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> found that the Free Press, a morning paper that has lost $ 100 million in nine years, was a failing newspaper under the 1970 Newspaper Preservation Act. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> approved a joint operating agreement between the Free Press and the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, owned by <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The partial merger was temporarily blocked by court order until <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Revercomb </PERSON> has a chance to rule on a legal challenge. <PERSON> Revercomb </PERSON> said he would issue a ruling by next week. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON>, an attorney representing <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> Citizens for an ndependent Press, charged that the two dailies engaged in a bitter war of price cutting to either put each other out of business or qualify for a lucrative joint operating agreement. `` Did <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> intend to give large corporations like <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> the opportunity to gain a <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION> simply by cutting prices, thus creating a record of loss?'' <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Millet </PERSON> said `` there absolutely was no evidence of collusion'' between the Free Press and The News, which was bought by <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> in 1986, several months before the joint operating agreement was formally sought. `` The fact that these two papers considered the option and discussed this over a period of time is not an argument that a <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION> should n't occur,'' <PERSON> Millet </PERSON> said. Those discussions were a `` natural consequence'' of the fact that both papers sustained losses while cutting advertising and circulation rates to gain dominance in the market, <PERSON> Millet </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON>, an elder statesman of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> who served as <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION> secretary under President <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, said the News had rejected several Free Press overtures to joint their production and commercial departments. The News was `` determined to keep the <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> as far down as they can because in the news business you try to become the dominant paper,'' <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON> said. `` As soon as you find yourself in the second position, you are probably on your way out.'' While the Free Press was locked in bitter competition with the News, `` every year except one, they lost more money than they lost the year before.'' `` Knight-Ridder, during the eight-year period, poured $ 176 million into the Free Press in an effort to keep it afloat,'' <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON> said. `` At the end of the period, the <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> was losing more money then they were at the beginning.'' <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> has threatened to close the Free Press if the joint operating agreement is not allowed to go through. <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON> said closing the Free Press would cost 2,200 jobs while between 600 and 800 jobs would be eliminated if the two dailies combined their business operations. <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON> argued that <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s decision was arbitrary because he ignored the administrative law judge's recommendation. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> disregarded the administrative law judge's conclusion that if the partial merger were not approved, the News, which has also posted significant losses, would eventually raise its prices, thereby allowing the Free Press to do the same, <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON> said many of the administrative law judge's conclusions `` got so far beyond the question of fact that you get into the realm of speculation.'' <PERSON> Millet </PERSON> said the opponents have to prove `` the decision is irrational, not that they do n't like it or they think the administrative law judge recommended a contrary result.''
