<HEAD>Bush Views Missile Engine Destruction; Hails INF Treaty</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: TOP 12 grafs new with Bush witnessing destruction of missile
engines, comments from vice president; picks up 4th graf pvs,
`Bush's embarrassing,' EDITS to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KARNACK, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Republican presidential nominee <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> today viewed the fiery destruction of a set of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intermediate-range missile engines and said the demolition marks `` the day we began to reverse the arms race.'' The vice president, who watched as the two <LOCATION> Pershing </LOCATION> missile engines were fired _ the first to be destroyed deliberately under the U.S.-Soviet arms reduction treaty, said this is `` one of those unique moments in the career of man, a moment when the tides of history turned, that a new future dawned.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> joined other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet officials on the reviewing stand at the <ORGANIZATION> Longhorn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ammunition </ORGANIZATION> plant here to witness the demolition of the two engines, which are among the 859 weapons that the two superpowers have agreed to destroy over the next three years. Peering through binoculars from a distance of about 1,000 feet, the vice president watched as the motor of a Pershing II missile engine was fired to burn up its fuel followed by the firing of a smaller Pershing 1a rocket engine. The destruction was accompanied by a thunderous blast that lasted about a minute and then a loud cheer from those on the reviewing stand. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has already demolished several of its counterpart SS-20 missiles under the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty signed last December. `` We, too, are sending our INF missiles to the junkyards,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` The missile stages we destroy today are just a beginning. It is a moment we will be able to tell our children and grandchildren about _ this was the day we began to reverse the arms race, this was the day we began destroying the weapons of destruction.'' Nuclear warheads of the missiles are to be dismantled under the same agreement. Even though the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign paid for the trip, the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> nominee was attending the event in his official capacity as vice president, aides said. <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s chief of staff, told reporters he did not believe the vice president had unfair advantage over <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> because of his ability to participate in the program. `` <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has been associated with the efforts to achieve an INF treaty for many years. It's something I think he is legitimately entitled to participate in,'' <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON> said. On Wednesday, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he `` just got messed up'' when he told an <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legion </ORGANIZATION> audience that it was the 47th anniversary of <LOCATION> Pearl </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Day </LOCATION> _ three months in advance of the actual day. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s embarrassing gaffe, which he corrected after noticing the perplexed expressions in his audience, happened when `` I wanted to work <LOCATION> Pearl </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> in and just got carried away,'' he told reporters traveling with him on Air Force Two. `` I looked up and saw incredulity on the face of one particular guy and I thought, ` Whoops! My heavens I've done it!' So I was glad to correct it.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> received a boost in the latest <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News-Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> poll, which showed the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> candidate ahead of <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Presidential </ORGANIZATION> nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> 51 percent to 43 percent. The survey of 1,104 likely voters was conducted Aug. 31 to Sept. 6 and had a margin of error of 3.5 points. The Post cautioned that the results may be unusual because many people were away from their homes during the Labor Day holiday. In an apparent effort to defuse <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> claims that he is insensitive to the concerns of working people, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> newspapers that he will soon propose an increase in the minimum wage. The administration opposes an increase, and campaign sources said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was expected to link the increase with a below-minimum training wage for new hires and for teen-agers. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told the B'nai B'rith convention Wednesday in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> that the treaty `` to eliminate a whole class of nuclear weapons'' could not have been negotiated from a position of weakness. `` Strength works better than weakness if you want to get both peace and security,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> did not refer to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> directly in his speech to the B'nai B'rith, a national Jewish service organization. But in his earlier talk to the American Legion convention in <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, he suggested his rival's defense policies would `` leave <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> hostage to Soviet ballistic missiles.'' He said Soviets were now deploying two new intercontinental ballistic missiles. `` So even with perestroika, Soviet military modernization has not slackened,'' he said. `` Soviet military spending continues to rise.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also: _ Told the B'nai B'rith that he opposes creation of a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> state but believes Palestinians `` must be involved at every step'' in the peace negotiations with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> _ Said anti-abortion demonstrators `` went too far'' in recent noisy protests against Democratic rival <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>.
