<HEAD>Floods Hit Florida's Central Gulf Coast; Thousands Forced To
Evacuate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with five grafs to UPDATE with most evacuees told
they'll have to wait another day; PICKS UP 4th graf pvs, `It is
...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRADENTON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Most of the 1,000 or so people evacuated along the coast learned today they'd have to wait another day to return to their homes, swamped by a four-day torrent that swept away a motorist and drowned a toddler. `` We have to make sure everything is OK before we let people back in,'' <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Rita </PERSON> <PERSON> Dralus </PERSON> said before some people were allowed to return this morning. `` There are water mocassins and there are gators because ponds have overflowed, and electricity and water definitely do n't mix.'' Much of the flooding in the <LOCATION> Bradenton-Palmetto </LOCATION> area of <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> subsided by late morning, and most roads were declared passable and reopened. All schools that had been closed Wednesday were reopened today except for <ORGANIZATION> Bradenton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, which had suffered water damage. The National Guard was put on alert Wednesday as residents bailed out from the 9 to 15 inches of rain that have fallen along the state's central <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> since Sunday, turning streets into rivers and spilling sewage into living rooms. It is the area's heaviest rain in a decade, surpassing the deluge that accompanied Hurricane <PERSON> Elena </PERSON> in 1985. `` We just can not handle all that rain,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Parks </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Manatee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>'s drainage superintendant. `` It's the worst we've had in the 11 years I've been here. The rain fell from a near-stationary cold front hovering across the central <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> peninsula. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> predicted that 4 more inches could fall