</ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> shelter at <ORGANIZATION> Manatee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> after his <LOCATION> Bradenton </LOCATION> duplex was flooded out. `` The water was halfway up my calf and that was inside the house,'' <PERSON> Hardin </PERSON> said. `` Everything on the floor was pretty much ruined. The sewer backed up. In the house, it smells like a septic tank. I do n't want to go back.'' Water depths of 4 to 5 feet were common on streets before levels began dropping as the steady rain turned into a drizzle Wednesday afternoon. `` We had police officers in dump trucks patrolling the city,'' said City Councilman <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wells </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Palmetto </LOCATION>, across the <LOCATION> Manatee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Bradenton </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> also opened three shelters in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION> as floodwaters left cars in some sections of south <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION> submerged to their windshields. Elsewhere in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, the bad weather was blamed for weakening the clay foundation under a 500-ton construction crane that toppled in <LOCATION> Gainesville </LOCATION>, trapping a 76-year-old woman in her car and pinning the crane's operator. <PERSON> Evelyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> was in stable condition Wednesday night after being trapped more than an hour, and the operator was quickly freed, <LOCATION> Gainesville </LOCATION> police Lt. <PERSON> Sadie </PERSON> <PERSON> Darnell </PERSON> said.
