<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Irish government refused entry to Jewish refugees from <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and was heavily influenced by its ambassador to <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, who said the Jews were a source of corruption, according to a new book. `` <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> 1919-1949,'' by historian <PERSON> Dermot </PERSON> <PERSON> Keogh </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Cork </PERSON>, cites previously secret state documents to show that the government regarded Jews as `` a potential irritant in the body politic'' who had `` disproportionate wealth and influence.'' The book, published Wednesday, says <PERSON> Eamon </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Valera </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> prime minister at the time, was advised by his ambassador to <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Bewley </PERSON>, a former ambassador to the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> and a Roman Catholic convert from Quakerism. He cites reports in the state archives in which <PERSON> Bewley </PERSON> blamed Jews for `` the appalling moral degradation'' of pre-Hitler <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and claimed that they creates `` grave moral scandals and are a source of corruption of the populations among which they dwell.'' <PERSON> Keogh </PERSON> writes that <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Valera </PERSON> did not share these views and frequently would `` deviate substantially'' from the policy. About 150 Jews from <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> were admitted temporarily, he says. But he also says de Valera rejected pleas from <LOCATION> Irish </LOCATION> Jewish leaders to give refuge to a German Jew who had jumped ship in <PERSON> Cork </PERSON> in 1939. The Jew ended up in a concentration camp, <PERSON> Keogh </PERSON> writes. He says there is evidence that government departments opposed any entry of Jews even after the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION>' extermination of Jews became known. The policy, he says, continued after the war. <PERSON> Keough </PERSON> quotes a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> memorandum saying Jews should be treated less liberally under the immigration law because `` the wealth and influence of the Jewish community in this country appears to have increased considerably in recent years and there is some danger of exciting opposition and controversy if this tendency continues.'' Even in 1953, a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> memorandum referred to Jews as a people who `` appear to have disproportionate wealth and influence,'' <PERSON> Keogh </PERSON> writes. <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, a country of 3.5 million, has about 1,900 Jews.
