<HEAD>New Jersey Allows Principals With No Teaching Experience</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM KRATTENMAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Aspiring principals for the first time will not be required to have teaching experience, under a new state policy. Educators said the policy makes <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> the first state to open the principal's office to non-teachers. The plan, approved Wednesday by <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jersey </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>, increases standards for all candidates but drops a requirement of three years' teaching experience. The plan will allow the new principals to get teaching experience as they go. `` These new standards create a rigorous procedure for preparing all future principals and, at the same time, open up the system so that local districts can select the best potential candidates, regardless of background,'' Education Commissioner <PERSON> Saul </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooperman </PERSON> said in a statement after the board meeting in <LOCATION> Jamesburg </LOCATION>. Principals without education backgrounds will be designated as being part of a `` pilot project.'' It is to be reviewed by an independent panel in four years, <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Shatzkin </PERSON> said. During that period, the state will allow the hiring of no more than 50 new principals who lack teaching background, he said. The applicants will be required to have a master's degree in management, however. Principals with less than a year of teaching experience will have to teach one class period a day for at least a year, and candidates with less than a yer of teaching experience will have to teach for two years. In addition, they will be required to complete 135 hours of graduate study in education during their one - to two-year residency <PERSON> Cooperman </PERSON> said the changes will give <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> schools a wider and better field from which to choose principals. <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Pipho </PERSON>, a spokesman in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> of the States, which follows school policies across the country, said he knows of no other state that allows non-teachers to be principals.
