<HEAD>Man Breaks Record For France-to-England Swim</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOVER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 23-year-old Briton today broke the speed record for swimming the English Channel from <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, making the crossing in just over eight hours. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Davey </PERSON>, a chemical engineer from <LOCATION> Folkestone </LOCATION>, swam in calm seas and clear weather from <LOCATION> Cap </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Griz </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nez </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, to <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON>'s Bay near <LOCATION> Dover </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, in eight hours and five minutes He cut by 10 minutes the record for a crossing from <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> set by <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Rush </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> last year. The fastest swim for a channel crossing in either direction was set in 1978 by <PERSON> Penny </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, while swimming from <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> in seven hours, 40 minutes. The distance from <LOCATION> Dover </LOCATION> in a straight line to the nearest point in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> is 21 miles, but winds, tides and currents usually add 10 miles or more to the distance for swimmers. <PERSON> Davey </PERSON>, an experienced long-distance swimmer, failed by 57 seconds on Saturday to break the all-time record for a crossing of the 10.5-mile long <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Windermere </LOCATION> in northeastern <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. He made the crossing in three hours, 50 minutes, and 53 seconds.
