<HEAD>Quayle Calls for Repealing War Powers Act</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Quayle speech in top 16 grafs, picking up in 5th
graf pvs, ``No matter; trims at end</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, who has concentrated on Democrat-bashing in recent days, switched today to a detailed national defense speech touting the Strategic Defense Initiative and calling for repeal of the War Powers Act. The Republican vice presidential candidate, in remarks prepared for delivery to the City Club of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, also said that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> allies should share more of the cost of their own defense. On SDI, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said, `` The next president should make every effort to determine whether he or his successor could develop and deploy a second red button _ not just the button of retaliation but the button of protection.'' The speech was designed to spotlight <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s experience as a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. He spoke in great detail on the justifications for SDI, popularly known as Star Wars, as well as other weapons systems and national security philosophy in general. He called for a cautious approach to U.S.-Soviet agreements. `` We must probe the Soviet position on START, working to conclude an agreement while modernizing our forces,'' he said. `` We must probe the Soviet position on conventional forces while continuing initiatives to strengthen our conventional force posture. And we must probe Soviet willingness to restrain their clients and to determine whether Soviet ` new thinking' will in fact lead to behavior that can lower the possibilities for regional conflicts,'' he said in the prepared statement. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s text did not mention Democratic presidential nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, whom he has heatedly attacked as being weak on defense in recent days. He attacked congressional `` interference in the president's ability to conduct foreign policy. He said the War Powers Act `` is unconstitutional and should be repealed or drastically rewritten.'' The act, enacted by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1973 over President <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s veto, is a Vietnam-era law limiting a president's ability to commit <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops to dangerous situations The law says a president must send a report to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> within 48 hours after <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military personnel are sent to areas of `` imminent hostilities.'' The forces would have to be withdrawn in 60 days, in some cases, unless <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> votes to permit them to stay. All presidents since <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> have argued the law is an unconstitutional restriction on the executive branch. There is widespread criticism _ from <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republicans </ORGANIZATION> alike _ that the law is unworkable and there is now a bipartisan push to rewrite the law, although there is not yet agreement on details. On Wednesday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> got a warm welcome from his colleagues his first day back on the job since becoming <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s running mate, but the message from <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republican Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> was mixed at best. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> praised <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> as `` a rising young star in our party'' at a Capitol reception, but later he stopped short of calling <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> an asset to the Republican ticket when pressed by reporters. `` I think he's becoming an asset,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said. Did that mean the senator thought <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> had achieved that status yet, he was asked. `` Becoming,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> repeated. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> told his <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> colleagues, `` I ca n't wait to get back out there'' on the campaign trail. There were cheers from the senators as <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> spoke, some of them calling out, `` Hear, Hear!'' `` No matter what happens in this election, the people who know me best and the people I am closest to are the people right here in this room,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said. `` I hope you never forget. Believe me, I'll never forget.'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said he would return to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for key <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> votes as he was needed. `` I know you've been on a roller coaster ride,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said as he welcomed the <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> senator back after a summer recess in which <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> became the party's vice presidential nominee. Since his nomination, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> has been dogged by controversies over his military service, personal life and academic record, and some in his own party have expressed skepticism about whether the 41-year-old senator should be on the ticket. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, a onetime presidential hopeful who was on <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s short list of vice presidential prospects, has himself expressed reservations about <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said recently that people of his generation might have problems with allegations that <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> used his wealthy family's influence to get into the National Guard during the Vietnam War. He repeated that view after the reception Wednesday, telling reporters, `` If he did get certain breaks ... that would create a problem in the minds of many, particularly, I would say, in my generation.'' At the reception, <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> presented <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> with a small fire extinguisher, which he said <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> could `` spray on the press from time to time.'' He also gave <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> a framed copy of the Pledge of Allegiance. The Republicans have criticized <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the Democratic presidential nominee, for vetoing a <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> bill that would have required teachers to lead students in the pledge. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> devoted his Labor Day fall campaign kickoff speech to the pledge.
