<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The 25th annual National Championship Air Races next week are expected to attract record crowds despite the tragic crash into a German air show audience. The possibility of a similar disaster is remote here because of strict <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and air race rules, according to <PERSON> Thornton </PERSON> <PERSON> Audrain </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Reno </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Racing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` The planes are not allowed to fly toward the crowd,'' he said Wednesday. `` In fact, they are only allowed to fly parallel to and away from the crowd. We've always been very safety conscious and have never had any spectators injured.'' Eight participants have been killed, however. <PERSON> Audrain </PERSON> said he expects attendance this year to at least match the record 148,000 who flocked to Stead Airport 10 miles north of <PERSON> Reno </PERSON> in 1987. Time trials for the various classes of airplanes begin Monday, and the races are Sept. 15-18. A record field of nearly 120 entrants is expected to compete at speeds of up to more than 450 mph for a total purse of $ 450,000, according to race officials. Entrants range from independently wealthy flying buffs to corporate sponsored pilots. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thunderbirds </ORGANIZATION> also are scheduled to demonstrate their precision moves, and stunt pilots will entertain between races. `` People expect the stunt flying. It's part of the show,'' Audrain said. At <ORGANIZATION> Ramstein </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, more than 50 people died after three jets from an Italian military precision flying team collided at an air show Aug. 28 and one hurtled into a crowd of spectators, exploding into a fireball. `` That type of maneuver would never be permitted under our rules,'' Audrain said. `` It would have to be a very, very unusual circumstance for the audience to be at risk at all. I just do n't see it happening `` We have insurance, although that would n't prevent an accident,'' he added. The air races began in 1964 with 24 entrants competing for a purse of $ 31,774. Since 1966, the event has attracted many of the best racers and stunt fliers in the world. The eight participant deaths during the history of the race included one just last year, a pilot whose plane crashed after an apparent engine malfunction. `` We have had some deaths associated with the races, but all in all we've had a very good safety record,'' Audrain said. `` Some things you just ca n't prevent, but with the strict <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> rules, we think we're as safe as you can get.''
