<FIRST>r i AM-Peru     09-08 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leftist Insurgency Could Lead To Civil War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSE GONZALES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Centuries of hate and discrimination between <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s rich and poor have spawned a vicious leftist insurgency that could lead to civil war, the head of a blue-ribbon <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> panel on violence warned Thursday. `` Either we make a concerted effort at a national plan for pacification ... or face the possibility of a country caught in a civil war,'' Sen. <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernales </PERSON> said in making public the commission's report. Poverty, racism and government corruption are other major causes of the eight-year insurrection of the <ORGANIZATION> Maoist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shining </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Path </ORGANIZATION> guerrilla group, said the study, conducted by a panel of 11 senators. `` Political violence in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> is not the result of poverty alone but of humiliation, oppression, hate between classes, racism,'' <PERSON> Bernales </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bernales </PERSON> said the 389-page report, which probes the roots of violence and offers possible solutions, is the most extensive of its kind ever undertaken in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>. The commission said the white ruling class has maintained the subjugation of Indian peasants in the Andean highlands first begun by Spanish conquerors and continued by the aristocracy. It said the peasants, who make up about 40 percent of <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s population, are the most uneducated, impoverished and ignored sector of society and are frequent objects of scorn `` This has become an intolerable humiliation. They are being pushed to the border and are questioning the existing order. Violence has resulted,'' the report said. The commission, which used government and private studies in its findings, said 11,605 people have been killed and property damage has reached $ 10 billion in the Maoist revolt. The panel said that the economy also has deteriorated dramatically. `` The country is in the same situation as it was 15 years ago. It has lost all movement toward developing,'' said <PERSON> Bernales </PERSON>. Mounting problems have sparked an exodus of skilled workers and professionals. The report said 125,000 Peruvians emigrated in the past four years, about half to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In a nationwide survey, which sampled residents of the terror-ridden mountain states of <LOCATION> Ayacucho </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Huancavelica </LOCATION> for the first time ever, the commission found 60 percent of <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s 20 million people believe the government has been ineffective in dealing with terrorism. The commission said the insurgency, repressive countermeasures by government forces and drug trafficking have sparked political instability and undermined participation in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s democracy. About 300,000 Peruvian families are linked to narcotics trafficking, according to the study. The peasants grow coca, the raw material of cocaine, on small jungle plots for their livelihood. The Shining Path recently opened a new front in the coca-growing zone. The commission urged greater efforts be made toward feasible crop substitution programs. It also urged government forces to reject illegal tactics in dealing with guerrillas. `` The state and society must stay within the law in defending itself,'' said <PERSON> Bernales </PERSON>. The states of emergency to counter rebels, now in effect in seven states where more than 40 percent of the population lives, should be phased out to strengthen respect for democracy, the commission said. The panel recommended a national consensus be reached quickly on how to resist the guerrillas, and it urged radical changes in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s rigid class structure. The commission also proposed that police and the military undergo training in respecting human rights.
