<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge was confronted Thursday with conflicting arguments over whether to let <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s two daily newspapers complete a partial merger approved last month by then-Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON>, attorney for a <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> group of readers and advertisers opposed to the arrangement, accused owners of the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> and the Detroit News of cutting prices to put each other out of business or eventually qualify for a lucrative joint operating agreement under the Newspaper Preservation Act. But a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> attorney, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Millet </PERSON>, said there was `` absolutely no evidence'' that the two newspapers had colluded. The arrangement approved by <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> before he left office would allow the morning <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, owned by <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, to merge its commercial and business operations with the News, bought in 1986 by <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> has threatened to close the Free Press, which has sustained $ 100 million in losses in nine years, if the partial merger is not allowed to proceed The deal was temporarily blocked by court order last month to give <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Revercomb </PERSON> a chance to consider the legal challenge by <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Citizens </LOCATION> for a Free Press. <PERSON> Revercomb </PERSON> said he would rule next week on the group's request for an injunction barring the merger. The <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> group of readers and advertisers charges that the two newspapers set out to try to put each other out of business by cutting advertising and circulation rates or to qualify for a joint operating agreement. `` <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION>'s strategy was to sustain short-term losses with its eye on very long-term profits'' under a joint operating agreement allowed by the law's anti-trust exemption, <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON> argued that <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s decision to allow the partial merger was arbitrary because he ignored the administrative law judge's conclusion that if the merger were not approved, the News, which has also posted significant losses, would eventually raise its prices, thereby allowing the Free Press to do the same <PERSON> Millet </PERSON> said `` there was absolutely no evidence of collusion'' between the Free Press and the News, which was not acquired by <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> until several months before the merger application was made in 1986. `` The fact that these two papers considered the option and discused this over a period of time is not an argument that a <ORGANIZATION> JOA </ORGANIZATION> should n't occur,'' <PERSON> Millet </PERSON> said. Such discussions were a `` natural consequence'' of the losses the two papers continued to suffer while waging the cutthroat newspaper war, he said. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON>, an attorney representing <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION>, said the News rejected several overtures from the <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> about forming a joint operating agreement. `` The News' answer was always: ` There is the door. Good-bye.''' said <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON>, an elder statesmen of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and a <ORGANIZ