<FIRST>u i AM-Amnesty-SouthKorea Bjt   09-08 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Amnesty-South Korea, Bjt,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Korea Urged to Release Political Prisoners, End Torture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has made significant improvements in human rights as it prepares to host the Olympics, but the government still holds 600 political prisoners and tortures some of them, <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. The human rights group said in a report that some political prisoners were jailed after unfair trials but that torture has decreased. Government sensitivity to world attention during the Sept. 17 to Oct. 2 Olympics may help improve the situation, but the Games do not guarantee changes, a representative of the London-based group said. `` The limits of freedom of expression have expanded ... the atmosphere is remarkably more free than before,'' <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> researcher <PERSON> Francoise </PERSON> <PERSON> Vandale </PERSON> said at a briefing on the report, entitled `` Detention of Prisoners of Conscience and Torture Continue.'' The report said <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> should release more political prisoners, end torture and ill-treatment of detainees, and change laws to allow peaceful expression of opposition to the government. Major political changes since last summer have ushered in some improvements in human rights, the report noted. The government of President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> Tae-woo came to power after <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>, then chairman of the governing party, pledged democratic reforms, including release of political prisoners, in response to violent demonstrations in June 1987. National Assembly elections last April gave the opposition a majority, a startling change for a country long ruled by a party with almost complete power. The assembly is debating several changes in laws on national security and demonstrations, and <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> called for amendments `` to exclude from their scope peaceful acts of opposition to the government.'' The changes have given political prisoners limited hope. `` There have been releases and amnesties but we think they've been too few,'' Ms. <PERSON> Vandale </PERSON> said. The government says nearly 1,300 political prisoners have been released since last year, but <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> says the number is only 400. The organization also said 4,000 former political prisoners' civil rights have been restored in this period, about half the number claimed by the government `` Arrests on political grounds have continued,'' with about 600 people imprisoned for political or trade union activities, the report said. Of these, about one-third have been convicted, as far back as 1958, for anti-state activities such as espionage, and given sentences from five years to life. Another one-third were arrested during nationwide strikes in 1987, and the rest are thought to be students arrested in the past year during anti-government demonstrations. Among the 600, <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> is calling for the release of 28 it has adopted as prisoners of conscience, and it is investigating the cases of another 70. <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> defines prisoners of conscience as those `` detained for belief, color, sex, ethnic origin, language or religion provided they have n't used or advocated violence.'' Students who threw rocks in demonstrations could not be considered, an official said. Constitutional amendments have strenthened laws protecting prisoners' rights, but `` in practice these rights are still not always respected,'' <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> said. It said relatives and lawyers have been denied access to any information about detainees, and prisoners have been isolated, beaten and deprived of sleep in the first days after their arrest. The group has not heard of water torture cases since several instances in the last two years in which police were arrested for torture or abuse of a detainee. Asked if <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> felt the government was making changes with the Olympics in mind, the researcher said, `` I suppose the government is sensitive to its political image, but I believe the release of political prisoners has more to do with the balance of political parties.'' She said that in the long term, `` of course the attention of the whole world matters ... but things have changed very quickly in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. We just do n't know what might happen after -LRB- the Games. -RRB-''
</TEXT>
