d in foreign affairs. On the other hand, they said by 51-42 percent that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` demonstrated poor judgment in the way he picked Senator <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> as his running mate,'' and agreed by 62-27 that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` is too willing to defend policies of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, such as the <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> arms deal, whether they worked or not.'' Asked who is the more decisive leader, 46 percent picked <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to 40 percent for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. In the August poll, it was 50 percent for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> to 39 percent for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. The remainder were not sure. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had the support of most Republicans and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was favored by most Democrats, as in August. But then independents were split, 49 percent for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and 46 percent for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>; in the new poll they went for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, 54-39. The August poll put the race overall at 51 percent for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> to 45 percent for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>.
