<HEAD>Educators Concerned About Censorship Efforts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Schools and libraries face growing pressure to censor the books children read, according to a report released Thursday by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administrators </ORGANIZATION>. `` Pressures that could result in censorship are increasing, and that has an adverse effect on the ability of the schools to provide a broad-based education for children, who will be our future leaders,'' said <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Krug </PERSON>, director of the association's office for intellectual freedom. This pressure comes from people who want to impose their views on the educational system by removing or restricting use of certain materials, according to the report, `` Censorship and Selection: Issues and Answers for Schools.'' The study was published jointly by the administrators group and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Library </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Over the past five years the number of challenges to library books and school materials increased by 168 percent, the groups said. In many cases, the study says, those seeking to censor materials see themselves as living in a hostile world, surrounded by enemies ... `` people whose world is filled with ` oughts' and ` shoulds' and any indication that other people are freer in their decision-making processes arouses in them severe feelings of anxiety and resentment.'' It is essential that schools reach out to these people before controversy can arise, the report suggests. Cited as a possible solution was one case where parents, who had heard reports of questionable material in some school books, were invited to the school to read and discuss the books in question. The teachers learned things from the parents, while the parents got to understand the books and came to trust the teachers, the report said.
</TEXT>
