 A memorial service will mark the 25th anniversary of a church bombing that killed four black girls and focused national attention on the struggle for civil rights in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>'s largest city. `` In embracing our history there is healing. Join us,'' reads an invitation from `` The Committee for Sept. 15,'' a group of black and white <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION> residents planning the ceremony. Four girls, ages 11, 14, and 16, were killed in the 1963 dynamite blast at the 16th Street Baptist Church. The girls were changing into choir robes in the basement on a Sunday morning when the blast tore through the room. Twenty-three others were injured. The bombing, one of dozens of racially motivated bombings in <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION> in the late 1950s and early 1960s, remained unsolved until 1977, when <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Chambliss </PERSON>, a white retired auto mechanic, was convicted of murder and sentenced to life in prison. <PERSON> Chambliss </PERSON> died in prison in 1985. Committee members said the remembrance will give blacks and whites a chance to remember not just the bombing but the civil rights struggle. `` We as a city are merely looking at ourselves, and saying that we remember,'' said committee member <PERSON> Bette </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>. The Sept. 15 event will feature a number of speakers, including the Rev. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Cross </PERSON>, pastor of the church in 1963 and now an official with the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION>. It will be held at <LOCATION> Kelly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ingram </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, a site adjacent to the church where a civil rights museum is planned.
