<HEAD>Activists Detained, Tutu Repeats Call For Election Boycott</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY_</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer_</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At least 27 black activists, including leaders of two banned organizations, have been detained in an apparent crackdown on opposition to Oct. 26 elections, newspapers reported Thursday. Anglican Archbishop <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>, one of several clergymen to defy emergency regulations by urging an election boycott, repeated his call Thursday. Addressing about 2,000 people at the predominantly mixed-race <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cape </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> said of next month's local elections: `` Please consider prayerfully what God wants you to do. We want to urge black people _ do not take part in a process which will perpetuate your oppression.'' The archbishop called on whites to join the boycott `` because the time of white politics is past.'' Police headquarters declined to comment on the reported detentions. It also has declined to give details of an investigation on whether <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> should be prosecuted for urging an election boycott. The anti-apartheid weekly New Nation said the detentions in the past two weeks are believed to be part of a government attempt to stifle opposition to the elections, which will mark the first time voters of all races go to the polls on the same day. Many blacks oppose taking part in segregated local elections as long as the black majority can not vote in national elections. By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services. Business Day, a <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION> newspaper, said the activists detained this week included <PERSON> Nkosi </PERSON> <PERSON> Molala </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Azanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Molala </PERSON>'s organization was one of 17 anti-apartheid groups banned in February from conducting any activities. It espouses the philosophy of black consciousness, or black self-reliance, developed by <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Biko </PERSON> before his death in detention in 1977. New Nation said 14 members of the South African <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, another of the banned groups, have been detained since last week. It said all top leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> now are in detention. New Nation, whose editor <PERSON> Zwelakhe </PERSON> <PERSON> Sisulu </PERSON> has been detained without charge for nearly two years, said 12 other activists from the <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> area were detained Wednesday. Two of them worked for the <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, a social service group which has expressed fears about the life of another <PERSON> black </PERSON> staff member, <PERSON> Stanza </PERSON> <PERSON> Bopape </PERSON>. Police say <PERSON> Bopape </PERSON> escaped three days after being detained June 9. His family and associates have not heard from him since, and fear he may have been killed. Security police have seized two tape recordings of a sermon given by <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> on Sunday in which he advocated an election boycott. Such calls are punishable by up to 10 years in jail. In his speech Thursday, <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> explained his defiance. `` It is not because <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> is trying to look smart,'' he said. `` I have a commitment and a passion for <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. We have the potential of being one of the greatest countries. My passion makes me able, whatever the penalties, to do what I believe God is asking me to do.''
