<HEAD>Capital Homicides Already At Total For Previous Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With almost four months remaining in 1988, the nation's capital has matched the number of homicides _ 227 _ that occurred in all of last year. The shooting death of the latest victim, a 17-year-old boy, was drug related _ as were three out of every five of the homicides this year, police said. `` Homicides and shootings go hand in hand with drugs,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> Chief <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>. In addition, the number of assaults involving guns have climbed to more than 940 so far this year, an increase of at least 54 percent, <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> said. `` The numbers are astounding,'' he added. Until the demand for drugs decreases, <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> predicted the city will see `` more homicides and more shootings.'' Police spokesman Capt. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> estimated that if homicides continue at the current pace, 335 persons will be killed in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> this year _ far exceeding the all-time record of 287, set in 1969. So far, 95 homicides this year, including the latest, remain unsolved. During August, there were 41 <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> homicides, a record for one month. The old standard of 37 was set in January. Police blame the upsurge on the growing popularity of crack, a highly-potent cocaine derivative. Many of the killings have come in turf battles as drug dealers have fought for selling rights for the drug in the city's 88 open-air drug markets, according to police. Of the 227 homicides so far this year, 156 have involved firearms, <PERSON> White </PERSON> said. Last year, guns were used in 129 homicides.
