 </ORGANIZATION> 2 to deploy its lander _ nicknamed the `` hopper'' because it literally would hop around the <LOCATION> moon </LOCATION>'s surface _ on May 25, <PERSON> Amorose </PERSON> said. Starting Oct. 10, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> was to help track both probes with its Deep Space Network, which consists of 230-foot, dish-shaped radio antennas in <LOCATION> Goldstone </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Canberra </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>; and <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Amorose </PERSON> said. The purpose is to help the Soviets `` navigate the spacecraft to their aim points at Mars'' and also help receive data transmitted to <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> by the two probes, he added. Solar <PERSON> Max </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Phobos </ORGANIZATION> 1 were to perform their solar studies later this month and again after <ORGANIZATION> Phobos </ORGANIZATION> 1 deploys its lander. The images from the spacecraft would allow scientist to study the narrow layer of hot gases on the sun's surface, said research scientist <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Strong </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Missiles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Palo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alto </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>.
