<HEAD>Judge Lifts 17-year-old Desegregation Order</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge has lifted a 1971 court order which required the desegregation of <LOCATION> Duval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> schools by crosstown busing. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> on Tuesday declared the school system is integrated and lifted the 17-year-old order, effectively removing the federal role in the district's desegregation efforts <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said he examined the status of students, faculty, transportation, extracurricular activites and facilities and determined that segregative practices do not exist. He rejected a 1985 lawsuit by the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> alleging that the original 1971 order was not being followed, and also then lifted the order itself. `` I live here, work here and go shopping here,'' the judge wrote. `` And the feeling I get is that the leadership of the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> is promoting this lawsuit, contrary to the rank and file of the black people of this community.'' Despite the ruling, <PERSON> Willye </PERSON> <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON>, the leader of the <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION> branch of the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION>, said the civil rights organization stands by its claim that the school system is not desegregated. `` We need to get the message out to the community that if this case is not appealed, we are going to be in a bind,'' she said, adding that a decision has not been reached on whether to appeal. As a result of the ruling, the school system will be free to redraw boundary lines, reduce crosstown busing and set its own standards for an integrated school system, said <PERSON> Jannell </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, an attorney for the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> and Education Fund in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> said Thursday that there would be no immediate changes, but he predicted that at least 25 percent of the students now being bused could be returned to neighborhood schools next fall. <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> said `` some busing for racial desegregation will continue in places where it is impossible to return to local schools and still keep an integrated school system.'' `` There's no question that every place where youngsters can return to neighborhood schools, a move will be made to do so,'' he said. The school system has 104,000 students, 35 percent of them black. About 30 percent of the teachers and 25 percent of the faculty are black, the court order said. Duval County buses 20,000 students each day. Officials have said that 45 percent of the busing is for integration. Many students riding buses from 25 minutes to an hour each way during the school year. In his ruling, <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said the school system had done a reasonable job of attempting to maintain racial balance at the schools, but he said practical problems got in the way. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> wrote that <LOCATION> Duval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> is so large, about two-thirds the size of <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, that it is difficult to rectify racial imbalance brought about by shifts in population patterns by busing.
