<HEAD>Mumps On Decline Again After Two-Year Increase</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release 6:30 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mumps, the once-common childhood disease, is declining again after two years on the rise, federal health officials reported Thursday. The <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> reported that mumps was down by two-thirds through the first 30 weeks of this year, with 3,166 cases reported in that time. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> also reported details of a mumps outbreak last year in three <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> financial markets, which illustrated the potential seriousness of the usually mild disease; the costs from the 116 cases averaged nearly $ 1,500 per patient. Mumps reached a record low in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1985, when 2,982 cases were reported _ down 98 percent from the 152,000 reported in 1968, the first year for the licensed mumps vaccine. Mumps reporting then rose over the next two years, to 7,790 cases in 1986 and 12,299 in preliminary reports from 1987. The cases reported in the first 30 weeks of 1988 mark a 67 percent drop from the same period in 1987, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said. The report made no speculation on this year's decrease. Recent outbreaks have occurred in high schools and on college campuses. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> noted that those outbreaks would include some people who may not have been vaccinated, because they were children between 1967, when the vaccine was first licensed, and 1977, when it was added to the list of vaccines recommended for all children over 1 year. One major outbreak last year occurred among an older group _ employees at three futures exchanges in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Between Aug. 18 and Dec. 25, 76 cases occurred at one exchange, 39 cases occurred at a second exchange and one more case occurred at a third exchange. The patients at the three exchanges _ which were not identified _ could not be positively linked, the Atlanta-based agency said. But researchers believe there may have been contacts between the three locations which could not be documented, said Dr. <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaplan </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> epidemiologist. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> was able to get vaccination information for 82 patients; more than one-third believed they had been immunized against mumps, but only three could prove it with records. `` The vaccine is how this could have been averted,'' Ms. <PERSON> Kaplan </PERSON> said. `` We suggest that adults have a complete immunization record -LRB- with all recommended shots -RRB-. ... But nobody thinks about adult immunization.'' The costs associated with the 116-patient outbreak _ including doctors' visits, hospitalization for nine patients, medications and missed work _ came to $ 120,738, or $ 1,473 a case, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said. That, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said, `` contrasted dramatically with the cost of mumps vaccine'' _ less than $ 5 a dose at public clinics, about $ 9 at a doctor's office. Mumps, which causes painful swelling in the neck, is usually mild but can cause serious problems in other parts of the body, particularly in adolescents and young adults. Serious complications can include deafness, orchitis in the testicles and meningitis or encephalitis in the nervous system.
</TEXT>
