<HEAD>Hinsdale Fire: Not Arson, But Probe Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The fire that cut telephone service for 42,000 customers for as long as 26 days was not arson but the cause is still unknown, according to a report Thursday. A preliminary report on the fire that destroyed an <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> switching station in <LOCATION> Hinsdale </LOCATION> offers few conclusions, but said, `` No evidence has been found that the -LRB- blaze -RRB- was deliberate.'' The report was prepared by <ORGANIZATION> Forensic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Annapolis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, and adopted as the official, preliminary summary by the staff of the <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. `` Clearly there is international interest in what is going on with this investigation,'' said <ORGANIZATION> ICC </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON>. `` Other telecommunications companies throughout the world want to prevent what happened in May in <LOCATION> Hinsdale </LOCATION>. `` This appears to be one of the largest telecommunications disasters that has ever occurred,'' he said. Forensic Technologies is expected to release its final report in November, <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON> said. The company was hired by the <ORGANIZATION> ICC </ORGANIZATION>, but <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> is paying the bill _ $ 290,000 so far, he said. At first, the Mother's Day fire was expected to be only a minor inconvenience for residents in <LOCATION> Du </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Page </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. But as <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> crews examined the damaged hardware, it was clear that what became known as the Great Phone Outage would last more than a few days. It was n't until June 4 that full telephone service was restored. The fire in the switching station started in the ceiling, in metal trays that hold cable above the telecommunication equipment, the report said. `` The fire department's use of water produced an immediate reduction of flame and heat,'' the report says. `` However, because the building power supply was designed to be very reliable, the source of electric power was continuous and the fire rekindled. <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> is conducting its own investigation and expects to release its report in November, spokeswoman <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON> said.
