<HEAD>Nicaragua, Indonesia Withdraw from Leadership Contest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION> withdrew Thursday as candidates to host the 1989 summit of nations professing non-alignment. The host nation automatically becomes the movement's chairman for three years Choice of a host country is a major issue at this week's conference of foreign ministers of the 101-member group Conference spokesman <PERSON> Nicos </PERSON> <PERSON> Agathocleous </PERSON> said neither country could muster enough support among the 95 nations and organizations represented at the four-day meeting. He said that left the field open for three compromise candidates _ <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Malta </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, whose late President <PERSON> Tito </PERSON> helped found the movement. `` There are very intensive and extensive consultations taking place to find a consensus candidate,'' said <PERSON> Agathocleous </PERSON>, a senior official of the <ORGANIZATION> Cyprus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. Some members oppose <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> because it was the summit host in 1961 and the tradition is for a nation not to repeat as chairman, but <PERSON> Agathocleous </PERSON> said that `` is not absolute.'' Sources said a decision is unlikely until Saturday, the last day of the ministers' conference.
