<HEAD>Army Flies Aid to Refugees; Flood Damage to Crops Estimated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An army airlift is carrying relief supplies to a refugee camp 500 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> where 40 people a day have been dying of starvation, a newspaper reported Thursday. <PERSON> Al-Ayam </PERSON> said the airlift had supplied the El-Meiram camp with canned goods and 1,000 sacks of sorghum so far. Relief official <PERSON> El-Tayeb </PERSON> <PERSON> Tahir </PERSON> told reporters a trainload of relief material arrived at El-Meiram last Monday and the <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> had been asked to allocate one train a week for the south. Thousands of southern Sudanese displaced by civil war, drought and recent floods have been moving north and many die of starvation or disease on the way. On Thursday, a month after the floods, the government said it estimates the damage to crops at about $ 365 million. Unofficial estimates put the cost much higher. The Rev. <PERSON> Aengus </PERSON> <PERSON> Finucane </PERSON>, director of the Irish aid agency CONCERN, said last month 40 people were dying every day at El-Meiram and starvation threatened about 2 million Sudanese in the south. According to <PERSON> Al-Ayam </PERSON>'s report, the army stepped in when international relief groups said they could not move goods to the south because of the heavy rains and floods. It did not mention the proximity of rebel <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> forces besieging <LOCATION> Wau </LOCATION>, 160 miles from the El-Meiram camp Rebel gunners shot down two civilian planes in 1986 and 1987 and the insurgent army, led by former Col. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Garang </PERSON>, has threatened to fire on relief planes. The rebels claim the government uses civilian aircraft to move ammunition and troops. <PERSON> Garang </PERSON>'s rebels began fighting the Moslem-dominated <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> government in 1983. They seek autonomy for the south, most of whose people are Christians or animists, and claim to control more than 90 percent of the countryside. <PERSON> Tahir </PERSON> said without elaboration that contacts were under way on arrangements for international agencies to fly aid to the south, but a Western official said privately the rebels were reluctant to approve such an airlift.
