<HEAD>Agreement Set On Streamlining Mortgages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The country's two largest purchasers of home mortgages announced Thursday that they have reached agreement on ways to streamline and simplify the often time-consuming process of obtaining a home mortgage. The agreement was reached between the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, known as <ORGANIZATION> Freddie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mac </ORGANIZATION>, and the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, known as <ORGANIZATION> Fannie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mae </ORGANIZATION>. Both corporations buy mortgages from primary lenders and resell them as mortgage-backed securities, thus increasing the pool of money available to make home loans. The two companies along with the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> have been participating for the past year in a task force seeking to standardize and simplify the mortgage application process. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Teutsch </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, an organization of local lenders, said the agreement between <ORGANIZATION> Freddie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mac </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Fannie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mae </ORGANIZATION> was an important first step and should set the stage for more progress in the future. The mortgage group estimated that further progress could eventually cut in half the time it takes to get a mortgage approved. At present, this waiting period ranges from 45 to 60 days. `` During the past 50 years, the mortgage origination process had become unnecessarily complicated for both consumers and lenders alike. It was time to turn back the tide of paperwork,'' <PERSON> Teutsch </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Teutsch </PERSON> said at a news conference that <ORGANIZATION> Fannie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mae </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Freddie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mac </ORGANIZATION> had both agreed to revise their mortgage eligibility requirements and underwriting guidelines to make them more uniform. This is critical because local lenders follow these guidelines closely in making home loans since loans that do not conform are not eligible to be purchased by the agencies for resale to investors. About two-thirds of all residential mortgages end up being resold into the secondary market. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Croft </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Freddie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mac </ORGANIZATION>'s executive vice president for operations, said that the task force had been useful in resolving several differences in underwriting guidelines between the two corporations. `` With <ORGANIZATION> Freddie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mac </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Fannie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mae </ORGANIZATION> having the same basic policies, lenders will not have to separate loans during origination based on which agency they plan to sell the mortgages to. That will streamline operations for mortgage lenders, resulting in better rates for borrowers,'' <PERSON> Croft </PERSON> said. Under the guidelines, the two agencies reached agreement on 20 different underwriting differences including loan-to-value ratios, multiple mortgages to the same borrower, seller contributions, age of credit documents and how to classify investment properties.
