<FIRST>r w AM-Guardianship     09-08 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Guardianship,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Civil Rights Measure Aims to Protect Elderly and Infirm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two House members on Thursday introduced a far-reaching civil rights proposal to protect elderly and infirm Americans from widespread abuse and neglect recently uncovered in the nation's guardianship system. Rep. <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., a chief sponsor of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guardianship </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Act </ORGANIZATION>, called the current system `` a national disgrace. `` Unfortunately, many state and local guardianship systems have become sleeping watchdogs of personal liberty,'' Pepper said in a statement. `` Even a convicted felon is guaranteed more rights in many areas than innocent elderly and disabled Americans who are subjects of guardianship proceedings.'' The bill, introduced on Pepper's 88th birthday, would safeguard the more than 500,000 Americans under guardianship and those facing the prospect. The elderly would have more rights and recourse under the bill, while guardians would have to meet new training and reporting requirements. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>, R-Pa., ranking Republican on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Special </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Aging, plans to introduce a similar guardianship safeguards bill early next week, a committee spokeswoman said People become wards of guardians if they are deemed incompetent to handle their own affairs. The guardian assumes their legal rights, possessions and decision-making authority; the ward typically is not permitted to vote, own property, marry or make medical decisions. Pepper said strong national safeguards against `` unnecessary and unduly restrictive guardianships'' are necessary because the system is so onerous. Rep. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonker </PERSON>, D-Wash., Pepper's chief co-sponsor, said the bill aims to `` restore guardianship to a system which does indeed serve to protect our nation's most vulnerable citizens. Specifically, the bill would require that anyone facing imposition of a guardianship receive adequate notice of impending proceedings, be represented by trained attorneys, be afforded an examination by an independent professional team, have the right to a jury trial, and have the right to prompt appeal of the decision or the choice of guardian. In addition the meaure would require that all guardians be of competent character, receive thorough training, provide at least annual reports on the financial and physical well-being of the incapacitated person, and be subject to annual review and automatic removal by the courts. The attorney general would enforce the legislation and could withhold federal money from states not in compliance with the act. The Pepper-Bonker bill was spurred in part by an Associated Press series that documented widespread abuses under the system, ranging from theft and fraud to neglect and simple incompetence. The AP series and its study of more than 2,000 cases were repeatedly cited in an explanatory document released by the health subcommittee chaired by Pepper. Among the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> findings: _ 97 percent of guardianship petitions are approved, indicating the deck is stacked against the `` accused. _ Nearly half the files on guardians were missing at least one annual accounting of money; only 16 percent of the files reviewed contained reports on the elderly ward's well-being _ 44 states require guardians to file regular accountings of a ward's money, but they were missing or incomplete in 48 percent of guardianship files examined The opening of guardianship was the last entry in 13 percent of the cases examined.
</TEXT>
