<HEAD>Pell Proposes Sanctions Against Iraq</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Iraq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Legislation imposing sanctions against <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> for its purported use of poison gas against Kurdish inhabitants was introduced on Thursday by Sen. <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON> <PERSON> Pell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-R.I. </LOCATION>, who told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> `` A crime of unthinkable proportions is emerging.'' `` For the second time in this century a brutal dictatorship is using deadly gas to exterminate a distinct ethnic minority,'' said <PERSON> Pell </PERSON>, the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` There can be no doubt but that the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> regime of <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> intends this campaign to be a final solution to the Kurdish problem,'' <PERSON> Pell </PERSON> said. `` While a people are gassed, the world is largely silent.'' The Iraqi embassy in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has denied that poison gas was used against the Kurds, asserting that such charges have been spread by Kurdish leaders living in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The Pell resolution declares that the Iraqi actions against the Kurds `` appears to constitute an act of genocide, a crime abhorred by civilized people everywhere and banned under international law.'' The resolution would ban all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, ban sales of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military equipment and ban the provision of credit or credit guarantees. It would prohibit the transfer of sensitive technology to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and bar the import of Iraqi petroleum products into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. It also would instruct the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> representative to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> to vote against all loans to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Pell </PERSON> noted that the Iraqi army moved against the Kurds after the Aug. 20 ceasefire in <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s war with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> with the objective of ending Kurdish control over a large section of northeast <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. `` The offensive was accompanied by the dynamiting of Kurdish villages throughout the region,'' <PERSON> Pell </PERSON> said. `` Poisonous gas was used on the people.'' `` It is said we do not have much influence over <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Pell </PERSON> said. `` This may be true, but I believe we must use whatever means at our disposal to get their attention. `` The Iraqi regime is a vicious dictatorship toughened by years of conflict,'' he said. `` Hand wringing alone will not change their course; immediate action is essential.''
