<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A vaccine for dangerous childhood diseases that include a form of meningitis has had mixed results, according to three studies in a prominent medical journal. But an accompanying editorial in Friday's Journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> says the results should not stop doctors from giving patients a new version of the vaccine. `` Like it or not, we must often make decisions in the absence of incontrovertible evidence,'' Dr. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mortimer </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, of <ORGANIZATION> Case </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>, wrote in the editorial. The original vaccine, for fighting a bacterium called Haemophilus influenzae type B, was first licensed for use in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in April 1985, largely because a clinical trial in <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION> had found it was 90 percent effective in preventing disease in children 18 to 71 months old and older. An updated version of the vaccine, approved in December by the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, is designed to improve protection for younger children. A committee of the <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> has recommended its use for all children at 18 months, officials said. The studies published in Friday's journal reviewed use of the original vaccine, which could be considered obsolete except for its cheaper cost, said Dr. <PERSO