<HEAD>Officials Seize 183 Pounds Of Heroin Found In Bean Sprout Machine</HEAD>
<HEAD>By ALAN COOPERMAN</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When the bean sprout washing machine was shipped from <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, police were waiting. When they opened its hollow steel rollers, they found 183 pounds of nearly pure heroin worth up to $ 260 million on the street. On Thursday, after six men were arrested in the case, state and federal law enforcement officials said the heroin seizure was one of the largest in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history. `` This is a very rare event to see this much heroin concentrated in one location,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>, special agent in charge of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. He said the heroin was probably enough to supply all the addicts in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> for more than a year. State police and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Customs officers, acting on confidential information, were watching for the machine when it arrived by truck at a <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> warehouse Aug. 30. According to court documents, they replaced most of the heroin with sand and waited for someone to claim the device. The heroin was hidden in the airtight, stainless steel rollers of the machine, said <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>. Four men were arrested Tuesday after they allegedly picked up the machine in a rental truck, distributed parts of it to two locations in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and then took the remainder to a scrap metal dealer. Undercover <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> agents later delivered some of the heroin to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, where they arrested two more men Wednesday night. All six suspects have been charged with possession of heroin and conspiracy to distribute the drug, said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney for <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON> said authorities believe the men are important figures in the drug trade, not merely `` mules,'' or carriers of drugs, and may have ties to Chinese organized crime groups. Police in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> have conducted several raids in recent days in connection with the case, but no arrests have been made there, he said. Five cardboard cartons of heroin were displayed at the news conference, along with the disassembled parts of the bean sprout machine, a contraption of prongs and rollers used by Oriental restaurants and produce merchants. `` The concealment effort was outstanding,'' said <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>, acting special agent in charge of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> for the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> region. Regional Customs Director <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Spayd </PERSON> said the amount of heroin seized was one of the largest in the country and the largest ever in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. Approximately 200 pounds was discovered in a shipment of ice buckets in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> in 1985, and 378 pounds was found in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> in 1971. Once diluted, the street value of the seized heroin would have been between $ 200 million and $ 260 million, he said. Police said the four men arrested in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> were of Vietnamese origin and gave their names as Hung Ta, 24; <PERSON> Dang </PERSON> <PERSON> Phu </PERSON>, 23; <PERSON> Hieu </PERSON> <PERSON> Ly </PERSON>, 24; and <PERSON> Tuong </PERSON> <PERSON> Luu </PERSON>, 45. They were in the custody pending arraignment Friday. The two men arrested in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> were identified as <PERSON> Wai </PERSON> <PERSON> Kwok </PERSON> <PERSON> Wong </PERSON>, 40, and <PERSON> Sik-Sze </PERSON> <PERSON> Yan </PERSON>, 36. <PERSON> McNamara </PERSON> said they are of Chinese origin. They appeared Thursday before a federal magistrate in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> but did not enter pleas and were held without bail pending a detention hearing Sept. 14.
