<HEAD>Post Office, Union Pursue Talks In Mail Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK McDOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Representatives from the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Communication </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> met Thursday in an attempt to end <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s week-old mail strike. International mail service remained at a standstill. But about half of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s 1,500 local post offices opened with non-striking and temporary staff who made sporadic deliveries, said <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Caroline </PERSON> <PERSON> Francke </PERSON>. The walkout began Aug. 31 as a 24-hour strike called in a dispute over bonuses paid to new recruits in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and southeast <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, where the cost of living is high and the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> has trouble attracting workers because of low unemployment. The strike now has no time limit, with the union demanding that the bonuses be paid nationally or not at all. `` Until there is a concrete framework agreed on over the central recruitment issue and a formula over getting postmen back to work quickly these exploratory talks will go on,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Francke </PERSON>. Union President <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Tuffin </PERSON> said Thursday, `` We are no nearer reaching an agreement.'' A spokesman would not confirm whether <PERSON> Tuffin </PERSON> joined the talks. About 100,000 of the union's 140,000 members stayed off the job Thursday, said Ms. <PERSON> Francke </PERSON>, and only one of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s 82 main postal sorting centers, in <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, opened for business. More than 100 million pieces of mail have piled up since the strike began, said Ms. <PERSON> Francke </PERSON>. Mail boxes around the country have been sealed. <LOCATION> Liverpool </LOCATION> police said strikers in that city, 200 miles northwest of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, behaved peacefully Thursday but picket line violence during the week led to the arrest of five strikers for disorderly conduct. The strike has disrupted business and the work of government agencies. A watchdog body, the <ORGANIZATION> Mail </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Users </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said Wednesday the dispute is costing British industry $ 43 million a day.
