<HEAD>Rains Continue Along South Atlantic Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The only rain in the nation Thursday was in the south <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> states and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Tropical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Storm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florence </ORGANIZATION> stalled far out in the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Florence </LOCATION> was about 500 miles south of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> on Thursday afternoon, with winds up to 55 mph. <LOCATION> Florence </LOCATION> has moved only slightly north since its inception Wednesday. As long as <LOCATION> Florence </LOCATION> continues in the Gulf, seas and swells will build throughout the Gulf of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. Rains in the south <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> coastal states and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> were gradually spreading to the north and west as southeast winds pushed a warm front back to the northwest. Breezy conditions continued across the north-central part of the nation. Winds gusted to 45 mph across parts of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>. A cold front extended across the upper <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> and the central <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>. The front has produced few clouds or rain due to the lack of moisture. Thursday afternoon temperatures were mostly in the 70s over the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> coastal states, the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> region and the upper <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> valley. Readings were in the 80s across the middle and lower <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> and the central Plains, with some lower 90s in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Temperatures were also in the 80s to lower 90s across the southern Plateau region. Temperatures were also in the 80s to lower 90s in southern <LOC