<HEAD>Soviet Jewish Mathematician Denied Exit Visa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 63-year-old Jewish `` refusenik'' dying of cancer has again been denied permission to leave the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for urgently needed medical treatment, a Soviet Jewry group said Thursday. The Union of Councils for Soviet Jews said it had learned that Soviet authorities have refused to grant an exit visa for <PERSON> Georgi </PERSON> <PERSON> Samoilovich </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> mathematician suffering from a deadly throat lymphoma. Last month, <PERSON> Samoilovich </PERSON> was removed from a waiting list to enter the <ORGANIZATION> Blokhin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> for treatment. <PERSON> Samoilovich </PERSON> has been seeking permission to emigrate to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> for 11 years. His wife, a physician, also is a refusenik. Americans who have been urging the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> government to let <PERSON> Samoilovich </PERSON> emigrate include Dr. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenbluth </PERSON>, chief oncologist at <ORGANIZATION> Hackensack </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Hackensack </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> `` We will be starting a last, desperate, all-out campaign to save his life, and I hope the world will be with us,'' <PERSON> Rosenbluth </PERSON> said. Soviet authorities have been denying <PERSON> Samoilovich </PERSON> permission to emigrate on grounds that he once did classified research work. But <PERSON> Rosenbluth </PERSON> noted that <PERSON> Samoilovich </PERSON> `` has not worked in his profession in over 10 years.'' `` The injustice of this case is overwhelming, especially in light of the new humanitarian facade the Soviets are putting on,'' <PERSON> Rosenbluth </PERSON> said.
