<HEAD>Deposits Flow Out For Third Consecutive Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Deposits flowed out of the nation's savings institutions for the third consecutive month in July, the government said Thursday. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said net withdrawals from the 3,088 savings institutions were $ 123 million in July after hitting a revised $ 3.3 billion in June, up from a previous estimate of $ 2.9 billion. In May, S & amp; L customers withdrew $ 1.1 billion. But, before that deposits grew for seven consecutive months as investors battered by the October stock market crash sought a safe haven for their money in government-insured accounts. <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> economist <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Barth </PERSON> said in a statement that a slowdown in withdrawals is normal for July. Consumers typically take money from their accounts at the start of summer to pay for vacations and other seasonal expenses. Mortgage lending by thrift institutions in July declined to $ 21.1 billion, 14 percent below the same month last year when many people were refinancing their mortgages, the bank board said. <PERSON> Barth </PERSON> said the drop in mortgage lending reflects the climb in interest rates this summer. The bank board also reported that the institutions' capital declined by $ 573 million in July after falling by $ 3.0 billion in June. For the first seven months of the year, it's off $ 6.4 billion. Declines in capital, which is the difference between an institution's loans and other assets and what it owes to depositors and other creditors, often reflect losses.
