<FIRST>u p AM-FEC-PACs     09-08 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FEC-PACs,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Growth In Spending By PACS Slows As Races Are Less Competitive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Spending by political action committees to influence the 1988 elections is on the increase, but the rise is far smaller than in previous years, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. Several political scientists said the money figures compiled by the <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> indicate that the PAC movement may be leveling off and reaching its saturation point. The <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> said that for the 18 months ending June 30, PACs representing business, labor, ideological and other interest groups spent $ 215.4 million, a 4.8 percent increase over the same period in the 1985-6 election cycle. The increase, however, was well below the 38 percent rise in <ORGANIZATION> PAC </ORGANIZATION> spending that occurred in the corresponding 18 months of the 1985-6 cycle when compared to the 1983-4 cycle, which itself was up 44 percent over 1981-2. Receipts by PACs showed a similar slowing in growth. The $ 266.6 million collected during the first 18 months of the current cycle was 4.7 percent above 1985-6, which saw 18-month receipts running 30 percent above 1983-4, which was 42 percent over 1981-2. As of June 30, PACs had given $ 94.9 million to candidates for federal office: $ 3 million to presidential races, $ 32.7 million to <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> candidates and $ 59.2 million to <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> candidates. This represented a 21 percent increase over the same 18 months in 1985-6. This rate, however, was below the 38 percent rise from 1983-4 to 1985-6 and the 49 percent growth from 1981-2 to 1983-4. Incumbent senators and representatives got got nearly 90 percent of the money contributed by PACs to congressional races in the first 18 months of this election cycle. Democrats led Republicans $ 60.9 million to $ 33.9 million. <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Ornstein </PERSON>, a congressional analyst with the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> think tank, said the double-digit percentage increases in PAC receipts and spending could n't continue indefinitely. `` We may have reached a saturation point,'' he said. `` That's good news for all of us except campaign vendors. <PERSON> Ornstein </PERSON> said that `` it's hard to say whether we've got a long-term trend.'' He said the reduced rates of increase could be partly attributable to `` to so few competitive races in the House. There is n't the demand from incumbents to put the screws to PACs.'' <PERSON> Janet </PERSON> <PERSON> Grenzke </PERSON>, a political science professor at <ORGANIZATION> Holy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Worcester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, said the figures could indicate `` the saturation point is nearing'' for PACs. `` Those people who were going to form PACs and who were going to participate in the political process through them have pretty much done so,'' <PERSON> Grenzke </PERSON> said. She said some political money that previously might have been channeled through PACs now could be ending up as `` soft money,'' the less-controlled and little-reported cash flow increasingly finding its way to places like political party committees. <PERSON> Herb </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>, a political science professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, said the number of PACs has leveled off, as has the number of PACs that are really active. `` A couple of hundred PACs do half the business,'' he said. `` There's an ingrown limitation on how much they can raise. ... While it's not at a standstill, the growth rate is n't as explosive. ... `` The PAC phenomenom is reaching a point of natural limits,'' said <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>. <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Huwa </PERSON> of Common Cause, the self-described citizens lobby that has been urging <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to outlaw PACs, said he was not heartened by the latest <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> figures. `` The first thing I look at is contributions to candidates, and that's continuing to grow,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
