<HEAD>FTC Aid Dismissed After Dukakis Letter</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: ADDS two grafs with comment by Clews.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> aide has been dismissed after sending a letter to newspaper editorial boards criticizing Democratic presidential nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> <PERSON> Clews </PERSON>, associate director for media relations, was dismissed on Wednesday, said <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> general counsel <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>, who said his office has been assigned to investigate the case. The letter was sent Aug. 4 by <PERSON> Clews </PERSON> to newspapers, offering to rebut criticism of the agency by <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and questioning statements made by <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in a controversy over advertising by optometrists. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> said he was not prepared to say whether <PERSON> Clews </PERSON>' action violated the Hatch Act, which prohibits political acitvity by federal workers. He said the investigation is continuing. Meanwhile <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> commissioners <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Azcuenaga </PERSON> and <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Strenio </PERSON> issued a statement dissociating themselves from a second latter sent by <PERSON> Clews </PERSON> to broadcast talk show hosts offering appearances by commission members. That letter contains a postscript saying that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has been critical of the commission and adds that commission members are willing to discuss the records of the <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> and of the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor. <PERSON> Azcuenaga </PERSON>, an independent, and <PERSON> Strenio </PERSON>, a Democrat, said they are happy to make appearances to discuss consumer affairs and other commission activities but will not discuss candidates for public office. <PERSON> Clews </PERSON> said later Friday, `` I do n't believe I violated the Hatch Act, and the general counsel himself has not said I violated the Hatch Act. And if I had violated the Hatch Act, there are certain procedures that by law they have to go through to give me a fair hearing. None of that was done.'' `` I think this whole thing is political and I was targeted because Commissioner <PERSON> Strenio </PERSON> and Commissioner <PERSON> Azcuenaga </PERSON> want to prevent Mr. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> from being criticized for his own attacks upon the commission. All I did was try to set straight the record of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said.
</TEXT>
