<HEAD>Attack On Police Station Injures Six</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with higher injury toll, CORRECTS
distance to Belfast, details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Five policemen and a girl were slightly hurt when a bomb planted in a van parked outside a village police station exploded Thursday, police said. The explosion, which caused extensive damage to the police station building and nearby houses, happened at the <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tyrone </LOCATION> village of <LOCATION> Coagh </LOCATION> 25 miles west of <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION>. A press officer at <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION> police headquarters, who in accordance with British practice declined to be identified, said a warning was telephoned to police at Coagh shortly before the blast. Police were evacuating people from nearby houses when the bomb went off. Police said the girl was believed to have been in a telephone booth near the police station at the time of the explosion. They did not have her age but said she was in her early teens. One of the five injured policemen and the girl were taken to a hospital at nearby <LOCATION> Magherafelt </LOCATION>. The other four injured policemen did not require hospital treatment. No group immediately claimed responsibility for the blast but suspicion inevitably fell on the <ORGANIZATION> Irish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. The mainly Roman Catholic IRA is fighting to end British rule in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>. It wants to unite the predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> province with the 95-percent <LOCATION> Catholic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> under socialist rule.
