<HEAD>Bush, Dukakis Campaigns Reach Tentative Agreement on First Debate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To give Bush reaction, INSERT two grafs after 9th pvs,
Brountas and...the debates, picking up 10th pvs, On Tuesday...and
Bentsen.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The presidential campaigns of <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> have tentatively agreed on Sept. 25 for the first debate between the two candidates, a <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> aide said Thursday. Both debates will be general in subject matter, in contrast to four years ago when the first was on domestic policy and the second covered defense and foreign policy, said <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodin </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s campaign spokesman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON>, chairman of the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign, said the two contenders will face each other in a televised debate at <ORGANIZATION> Wake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Winston-Salem </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> N.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brountas </ORGANIZATION> said their second debate would be either Oct. 13 or 14, depending on the length of the American League baseball playoff series which will be televised in prime time. The debate between vice presidential candidates <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> is expected to take place during the week of Oct. 3. The two campaigns have not reached agreement on the location for the second presidential debate and the vice presidential encounter, he said. `` We are still discussing format, staging and the length of the debates and we will continue to carry on those discussions,'' <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> said after meeting with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s campaign chairman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>. `` We believe we made good progress. This will be an opportunity for the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people to see presidential candidates debating face-to-face and man-to-man.'' The <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign wanted at least one more debate, with the first to be on foreign policy and national security issues, but that was rejected by the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign. <PERSON> Brountas </PERSON> and <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> emphasized that nothing is finally settled until they have agreed on all aspects of the debates. But <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said Thursday night: `` It sounds very good. Got the right number.'' Additionally, a statement released on <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Two </ORGANIZATION> said, `` I congratulate our negotiators on working out a formula for the number and timing of debates which certainly has my support.'' On Tuesday, after weeks of negotiations, the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign said it was willing to accept the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign's offer of two presidential debates as well as one encounter between <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>. The first debate will be sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Presidential </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Debates </ORGANIZATION>, a group headed by the chairmen of the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> and Democratic parties. The commission also was likely to end up as sponsor of the vice presidential debate. The League of Women Voters will sponsor the second presidential debate. League president <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON> said, `` The league is pleased that it's now official that the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> public will see at least one non-partisan debate this fall.'' She urged the campaigns to include the league in discussions on format. Last spring, the league suggested 90-minute debates with a single moderator rather than a panel of reporters such as used in past presidential debates. <PERSON> Goodin </PERSON> said the site of the second presidential debate would likely be on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>. Meanwhile, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> president <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Gartner </PERSON> issued a statement saying the network would not be able to televise the first debate live because it would conflict with its commitment to cover the Olympic Games. `` NBC News will run a taped replay of the first presidential debate between <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> that now has been scheduled for Sunday, Sept. 25,'' <ORGANIZATION> Gartner </ORGANIZATION> said. `` <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> has long been committed to broadcasting the Olympics, whose dates were known by both political parties.''
