<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 River levels were stable or receding Thursday and the <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION> airport reopened so relief supplies can be flown in, but distribution of aid to flood victims was slow and the death toll continued climbing. The government said 609 people have died in floods that began with the annual monsoon season in June, tapered off, then resumed in devastating fashion Aug. 27. Daily tallies by <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION> newspapers total more than 1,300, which is considered more accurate. Information Minister <PERSON> Mahbubur </PERSON> <PERSON> Rahman </PERSON> said Thursday 510 people drowned, died of snake bites or were killed when their houses collapsed. The government health center reported 99 deaths from diarrhea caused by drinking polluted water that flooded three-quarters of the country's 55,000 square miles. Health center officials reported 135,537 known cases of diarrhea nationwide, an increase of 15,715 in the previous 24 hours, but that includes only areas in communication with the capital. Officials say about one-quarter of <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>'s 110 million people are homeless. Many still are stranded on rooftops, in boats and on the rare patches of high ground in <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>, most of which is a vast river delta. Water levels in flood areas range from a few inches to more than 10 feet. <PERSON> Rahman </PERSON> insisted there was no shortage of water purification tablets, but his assertion seemed questionable. More than two dozen people interviewed at random Thursday in relief camps, flooded buildings and on rooftops in <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION> said they had no purification tablets and were drinking water that could be dangerous. `` Most of us have fevers and headaches,'' said <PERSON> Lily </PERSON>, a 17-year-old seamstress camping out at the Fair Fashion company factory with 10 co-workers. She said they paid 31 cents a day for about five gallons of tap water. <PERSON> Lily </PERSON> and a co-worker, 20-year-old <PERSON> Shamima </PERSON>, said they had heard of water purification tablets, but <PERSON> Lily </PERSON> said `` No one has given us any and we do n't have enough money to buy any.'' A diplomat from a Western nation that has tried to buy water purification tablets for relief distribution reported searching in vain for sufficient quantities in <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> and nearby countries. Representatives of other aid donors made similar reports, all on condition of anonymity. Pledges of disaster aid reached a total of at least $ 60 million Thursday, according to figures for individual nations reported by <PERSON> Rahman </PERSON>, the information minister. Included are $ 16.9 million in goods and cash from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, $ 3.6 million from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and $ 6.5 million each from <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crescent </ORGANIZATION> societies. Much of the aid will take the form of food, blankets and medicine. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> said it will send $ 11.9 million in new aid. The <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> on Thursday that the aid supplements $ 800,000 already pledged. Prospects for getting it to <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> brightened with the opening of <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION>'s airport to all aircraft. More than half the 10,000-foot runway was flooded this week, and only helicopters and smaller commercial aircraft were landing. The World Food Program issued a statement in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> saying the greatest problem is moving the aid to where it is needed. `` Relief distribution is being carried out by boats, barges and tugs and a very limited number of helicopters,'' the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> agency said. `` The government of <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> has appealed for more logistical assistance.'' <PERSON> Rahman </PERSON> told reporters neighboring countries agreed to study the flood problem in an effort to control the annual deluges carried by rivers that originate in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>. He said the problem was put on the agenda of the December meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Asia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperation </ORGANIZATION>. The three mightiest rivers that run through the country to the Bay of <LOCATION> Bengal </LOCATION> are the <LOCATION> Ganges </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brahmaputra </LOCATION> and Meghna. Floods are a problem every monsoon season, but the inundation this year is the worst for many years in <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>, whose rivers cover 10 percent of its territory even in normal times. Rapid deforestation in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> has contributed to the problem because bare soil can not retain as much water, according to geographers, government officials and <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> specialists. A report from the <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> flood warning and forecast center said the <LOCATION> Ganges </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Meghna </PERSON> continued receding slightly Thursday and the <LOCATION> Brahmaputra </LOCATION> held its level, with all three still above flood stage.
