<BYLINE>By DAVE PEGO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A transcript of cockpit conversation on <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> Flight 1141 reveals the crew knew their jetliner was in serious trouble about 21 seconds before it crashed Aug. 31 at <LOCATION> Dallas-Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, a newspaper reported Thursday. The transcript of a tape shows that about nine seconds after an apparently normal takeoff, a cockpit alarm showed the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 was not able to gather enough speed to stay aloft, the <ORGANIZATION> Dallas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> reported. The Salt Lake City-bound plane exploded and exploded and broke apart on impact, killing 13 of the 108 people on board. Eleven secords before impact, Capt. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Lon </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> exclaimed, `` We're not gunna make it!'' One of the final entries on the transcript appears to be a scream. The unauthorized release of the transcript drew sharp criticism from <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazor </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, who warned, `` There will probably be some repercussions.'' It will be months before investigators pinpoint the cause of the crash, but two primary suspects have emerged. They are wing flaps, designed to give the plane lift, and engine problems during the flight. The transcript reveals that flight engineer <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Judd </PERSON> and co-pilot <PERSON> Carey </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON> went through a standard preparation checklist. In the transcript, <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON> told <PERSON> Judd </PERSON> that the flaps were extended in the correct position for normal takeoff during the checklist less than a minute before the plane received permission for takeoff. <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> investigators said last week that the cockpit recording indicates there were two compressor stalls, which are disruptions of air flow, one each in two of the engines. The transcript, however, notes five possible compressor stalls within six seconds, a set of two followed within seconds by three more, the newspaper reported. Investigators have not been able to determine whether any compressor stalls actually occurred, safety board officials said. The engines are to be tested at the <ORGANIZATION> Pratt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> Whitney </LOCATION> manufacturing plant in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mazor </PERSON> said he believes the transcript, which he said appears to be a very relevant portion of the cockpit tape, may have been released `` to point the finger -LRB- of blame -RRB- away from whoever was doing the leaking,'' but said he would not speculate on who that may have been The release of one piece of evidence in an investigation that make take nearly a year is `` folly'' and may lead people to draw wrong and unfair conclusions, <PERSON> Mazor </PERSON> said. `` This has happened many times in the past, and we've complained many times in the past,'' <PERSON> Mazor </PERSON> said. He said the pilots union may consider filing a complaint with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, which is investigating the crash, about the transcript's early release. `` We got it from an investigator,'' said <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Herndon </PERSON>, an assistant managing editor of the <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>, but the newspaper would not disclose what agency the investigator worked for. A spokesman for the transportation safety board in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, said the board also is upset that a major portion of the transcript was leaked to the newspaper. `` We're upset because that transcript is an unauthorized, preliminary and incomplete version,'' said the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Benson </PERSON>. `` By law, that transcript is not to be released for 60 days. We make every effort to ensure the transcript is confidential.'' <PERSON> Benson </PERSON> said there is no way to determine who gave the transcript to the <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>. `` A number of parties have access to that transcript,'' including the pilots union, he said. <PERSON> Benson </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> officials are reviewing security procedures to see if they must be changed to prevent such documents from being leaked to the press in the future.
