<NOTE>EDS: Leads with nine grafs adding detail, eyewitness account;
picks up 4th graf pvs, Rowan, 52; Adds byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SHERI PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Syndicated columnist <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> was rushed to <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> when he fainted after giving a speech Thursday night, hospital officials said. <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON>'s condition and the cause of his collapse were not immediately available, but <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Kurtzke </PERSON> said the columnist was `` alert, he's conscious, he's sitting up. An ambulance dispatcher, who would not give his name, said <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> was taken to the hospital about 9:11 p.m. EDT for apparent heat exhaustion. <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> was leaving a lecture hall at <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> after giving a speech on the presidential campaign when he collapsed, a student who was nearby said. `` He walked up the stairs, paused, and was leaning forward over a sign,'' said <PERSON> Michelle </PERSON> <PERSON> Karpf </PERSON>, a freshman at American. `` He said, ` Oh, it's kind of warm in there,' and he was n't feeling well,'' she said `` I looked back over, and he was lying on the ground.'' `` He was holding his chest,'' <PERSON> Karpf </PERSON> said. `` Nobody really knew what was going on. People were running around going, ` Does anybody know CPR?''' About a dozen people were around <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> trying to ask questions when he collapsed, she said. `` He was conscious when they took him away,'' in the ambulance, <PERSON> Karpf </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON>, 52, has been the target of national publicity recently for shooting a teenage intruder who had taken an unauthorized midnight dip in <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON>'s back yard swimming pool. The columnist, generally known for his liberal views and an outspoken opponent of handgun use, is scheduled to stand trial Sept. 22 on charges that he used an unregistered handgun and ammunition in the June 14 shooting. <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> has argued that the weapon and bullets were given to him by his son, <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agent, who has said he was told by <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> officials that he did not have to register the weapon. The district's far-reaching 1976 handgun ordinance requires that all weapons be registered. If convicted on both misdemeanor charges, <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> faces a maximum penalty of two years in prison and $ 2,000 in fines.
