<HEAD>Storm Florence Drifting North In Gulf</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to UPDATE with 10:30 p.m. EDT position;
ADDS 3 grafs on tropical depressions forming.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tropical Storm <LOCATION> Florence </LOCATION> moved north in the southern <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> on Thursday, and forecasters said high-level winds were preventing it from strengthening as much as expected. At 10:30 p.m. EDT, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hurricane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> reported <LOCATION> Florence </LOCATION> had 55 mph winds and was drifting north at 5 mph, about 375 miles south of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>. The storm center was near latitude 24.5 north and longitude 89.2 west. Forecaster <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Gross </PERSON> said air currents high above <LOCATION> Florence </LOCATION> were blowing the top off its thunderstorms, keeping winds from intensifying to the 74 mph level that would classify the system as a hurricane. `` Right now it's maintaining the status quo,'' <PERSON> Gross </PERSON> said. He added that because of weak steering currents, it was impossible to predict where the storm was headed. `` We're still looking at a threat, but we do n't know what direction it is going to take,'' <PERSON> Gross </PERSON> said. He said it was not unusual for a storm to stall in the Gulf for several days before moving toward land. The <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parks </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday that <LOCATION> Grand </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Isle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> would be closed Friday because of high tides caused by the approaching tropical storm. Spokeswoman <PERSON> Debbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodiel </PERSON> said she did not know how long the park, which is on the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, would be closed. <LOCATION> Florence </LOCATION> is the sixth named storm of the 1988 Atlantic hurricane season. Only Debby, which also formed in the Gulf, reached minimal hurricane status briefly. The 12th and 13th tropical depressions of the season formed in the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> late Thursday afternoon. The 12th was centered about 300 miles east-southeast of <LOCATION> Barbados </LOCATION> with top winds of about 30 mph. The depression was drifting westward at 10-15 mph and was expected to continue this motion for the next 24 hours. The 13th depression was located about 400 miles northeast of the <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Verde </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> off the west coast of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, moving north at 20-25 mph with winds of 35 mph. The system was not expected to intensify, forecasters said.
