<HEAD>Justice Department Charges LA County With Vote Bias Against
Hispanics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> sued <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and its top officials Thursday, alleging that the county's 1981 redistricting plan has denied Hispanics equal voting rights The lawsuit, filed in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, seeks to invalidate the electoral boundaries set for the county's five elected supervisors, and to devise a new plan that complies with federal law. <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supervisors </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Deane </PERSON> <PERSON> Dana </PERSON> said the lawsuit was expected, and added it is `` unfortunate that the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has elected to take its action so near to the 1990 census.'' Supervisor <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonovich </PERSON> agreed, saying `` It makes more sense to wait 16 months for the next census than to use antiquated statistics from 1980 as the basis for reapportionment.'' <PERSON> Antonovich </PERSON> also denied that there has been any pattern of racial discrimination by the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supervisors </ORGANIZATION>. However, leaders of local Hispanic and civil rights groups welcomed the suit as long overdue. `` I think it makes it utterly uncontestable that there can be a continuation of the white enclave that has governed <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenbaum </PERSON>, an attorney with the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. The 1981 districts were `` gerrymandered to dilute the power of latino communities to elect a leader of their own choosing,'' said <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> representative for the <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Latin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION>. A discrimination case also was filed against the county last month by the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Mexican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>, which called the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supervisors </ORGANIZATION> `` the most exclusive, most powerful whites-only club in the nation.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s suit most likely be consolidated with the suit filed by the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> MALDEF </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Rosenbaum </PERSON> said. The county, which has an annual operating budget of about $ 8.9 billion, comprises an estimated 8.5 million residents, with each supervisor representing between 1.6 million and 1.7 million people, <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> said. A similar <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> discrimination suit was filed aginst the city of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> in 1985, leading to a settlement that radically revised <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> districts in the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fernando </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. The federal lawsuit charges that the county's electoral plan fragments the county's geographically cohesive Hispanic community, thus denying Hispanics an equal opportunity to participate in the political process and to elect candidates of their choice to the county governing body. Named as defendants, in addition to the county, were the Board of Supervisors; <PERSON> Dana </PERSON>; <PERSON> Antonovich </PERSON>; and Supervisors <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schabarum </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON>, <PERSON> Edmund </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON>, and Registar-Recorder <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Weissburd </PERSON>. <PERSON> Schabarum </PERSON> did not immediately respond to a telephone call seeking comment, and <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON> declined to comment. <PERSON> Hahn </PERSON> said in a prepared statement, `` I believe this could have been avoided if this past June 21st, the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supervisors </ORGANIZATION> had approved my motion to place a measure on the November ballot to expand the board to seven members.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> suit alleges that in 1970, Hispanics numbered 1,289,311, or 18.3 percent of the total population. In 1980, the suit says, the county's Hispanic population rose to 2,066,103, or 27.6 percent of the total population of 7,477,503. Blacks comprised 12.4 percent, or 926,361, and Asians and <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islanders </ORGANIZATION> 5.8 percent, 434,850, of the 1980 population. The suit says the Hispanic population stretched from the City of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> on the west to the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gabriel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> on the east, comprising about 73 percent of the more than 1.2 million people residing in the 230 contiguous census tracts and constituting what is called a `` community of interest.'' The 1981 reapportionment plan adopted by the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supervisors </ORGANIZATION> divided the concentration of Hispanic voters into three districts, with the result that <PERSON> Hispanics </PERSON> did not constitute a voting-age majority or plurality in any of the five single-member districts. <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> charged that the county also has systemically discriminated against Hispanics in its employment policies. He cited a recent study that found that Hispanics make up about 18.3 percent of the government's work force, while county hiring goals call for a 27.6 percent representation. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> complaint says that non-partisan elections in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, including those for the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supervisors </ORGANIZATION>, are characterized by patterns of racial and ethnic bloc voting.
