<HEAD>Night Ark: A Unique Fusion of Jazz, Armenian Melodies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ara </PERSON> <PERSON> Dinkjian </PERSON>, leader of the group Night Ark, talks about his music by first explaining what it's not: pop, jazz, folk or classical. Yet the lyrical and often haunting compositions of the band meld them all into a curiously attractive, eclectic fusion of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and Western styles. `` You hear a very strong Middle Eastern, Armenian flavor with all of the other elements creeping in and out'' of the music of Night Ark, says <PERSON> Dinkjian </PERSON>. `` Most Americans have a further history in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> or in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> that's a part of them. What I'm doing is opening my eyes and my heart to everything that I am and have been,'' he said. <PERSON> Dinkjian </PERSON>, who lives in <LOCATION> Nutley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, has a diverse musical background. At age 5 he performed at the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION>'s Fair as part of an Armenian ensemble and grew up listening to the Beatles and jazz. He studied Western classical music in college. In Night Ark, <PERSON> Dinkjian </PERSON> plays a variety of exotic <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> stringed instruments _ oud, cumbus, canoon, saz _ and writes and arranges most of the four-piece band's music. Keyboardist <PERSON> Armen </PERSON> <PERSON> Donelian </PERSON> and percussionist <PERSON> Arto </PERSON> <PERSON> Tuncboyaci </PERSON> share <PERSON> Dinkjian </PERSON>'s Armenian heritage, while bassist <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Schuller </PERSON> finds in Night Ark an opportunity to explore new sounds and technique. While the band members decline to call their music jazz, they perform mostly in jazz clubs, and Night Ark's two albums on the RCA Novus label are targeted primarily at jazz audiences. Those audiences, <PERSON> Dinkjian </PERSON> says, are generally receptive to Night Ark's often unconventional rhythms and melodies At its best, Night Ark plays a distinctive and frequently compelling music reminiscent of the Turkish-inspired jazz played a number of years ago by flutist <PERSON> Herbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mann </PERSON>. But at its worst, the band drifts into lazy renditions of timeworn pop standards, producing a music that ends up sounding like some uninspired New Age elevator music. `` The major disappointment is in the squandering of talent and ideas on a lame version of <PERSON> Carole </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>'s ` You've Got a Friend,''' says <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinnally </PERSON> reviewing Night Ark's second album, `` Moments,'' in <LOCATION> Jazziz </LOCATION> magazine. But, performing recently at the jazz club Fat Tuesday's, Night Ark relied on its original compositions to charm receptive listeners. Night Ark _ the name is a reference to biblical <PERSON> Noah </PERSON>'s Ark, which, legend has it, came to rest on <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ararat </LOCATION> _ retains several <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> musical fundamentals to produce its sound. `` Between two adjacent notes on a piano, there's an infinite amount of notes'' that are inaccessible to Western instruments but can be played by <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> musicians, <PERSON> Dinkjian </PERSON> said. `` Sometimes when people hear an Arabic song it sounds out of tune,'' he said. `` The reason why my music does n't sound strange is that I have slipped in all of those funny notes but carefully added the harmony behind it. We've kind of buffered it.'' Night Ark also employs rhythms unusual in Western music. `` This is not a jazz fusion gimmick; this is the beat I was brought up with,'' <PERSON> Dinkjian </PERSON> said. The insistent percussion `` is not alienating the Western audience, but tries to bring them in and say ` Welcome. You're going to like this.'''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Tues Sept. 20</NOTE>
