<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 17-18, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Voyager Gives Huge Impression</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto and LaserGraphic</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANN M. JOB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It does n't seem quite right to use the word huge when talking about a minivan, but that's the impression the 1988 <ORGANIZATION> Plymouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voyager </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> LE </ORGANIZATION> conveys. It also is comfortable, easy to drive and versatile. Want to take that antique table -LRB- with two leaves and four chairs -RRB- off <PERSON> Aunt </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON>'s hands? Pull out the two back seats of the van and tuck the dining set inside for the trip home. No problem. And the furniture wo n't get wet or dirty, as it would in the back of a pickup during inclement weather. Have five young ballplayers to take to the park? Put the rear seats back in and there's room for equipment and another adult _ and no one is cramped. It's no wonder <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has sold more than 1 million of these little-big gems since the automaker pioneered the minivan concept in the 1984 model year. Today, bigger automakers such as <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> have joined the market, but <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> retains the sales lead. <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION>'s van is sold in smaller quantities and has a higher base price for the cheapest passenger model -LRB- about $ 13,200 vs. about $ 11,000 for a <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-. The <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> downsized vans are rear-drive and a bit larger than <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s. One auto analyst has called the minivan the product success of this decade, and some analysts predict annual industry sales of 1 million in the next decade. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s idea for the minivan was to provide a fuel-thrifty way to cart around passengers and cargo comfortably in a roomy vehicle that would drive like a car and fit in a garage like a car. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> has stayed true to that concept, as the test <ORGANIZATION> Plymouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voyager </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> LE </ORGANIZATION> bore out. It was easy to drive and felt like a car, even during difficult parallel parking maneuvers. Driving in some other, especially full-size, vans can give a distinct bus-like feel as you turn the steering wheel and maneuver. Getting in and out of the Voyager was uncomplicated compared with some other vans where you have to climb up to enter and take a flying leap to exit. But like other vans and unlike a car, the Voyager _ 64.4 inches tall _ offered a good view of the road ahead. I appreciated being able to spot potential slowdowns in traffic and parking spots in shopping center aisles. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Jakobowski </PERSON> noted company research shows the low step height and low loading height are among the main reasons for the minivans' popularity. Women like that, he said, adding that 37 percent of buyers are female. Buyers' median age is 39, with median annual income of $ 45,000, he said. Fifty-six percent are college graduates and as many as 45 percent have professional-technical-managerial jobs. The Voyager test vehicle had superb fit and finish, inside and out. The side door slid open easily for passenger exit. The rear seats were arranged so two people could sit comfortably in the middle seat and three adults could fit in the seat behind them. Both seats could be removed with a bit of effort after detaching locks that held the seats to hooks in the floor. Be sure to check that the locks hold when replacing the seats or, whoa, you might flip backwards. Bucket seats were in the front, with space between them so a person could climb into the back without going outside. But the van's roofline is low, so adults do have to hunch over when moving about inside. There was some room behind the rear seat for cargo storage, enough to stand up several grocery bags. If more room is needed, there's a lever to pull so the the rear seat advances on a track. The seat back also can be folded down. In the 1987 model year, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> also introduced a longer minivan, the Grand Voyager, which is 14 inches longer than the regular Voyager and offers more cargo space behind the rear seat. Both the regular and elongated vans have a lifting rear door so you do n't have to hoist items up and over the vehicle body. I also appreciated the rear window being all one piece. In some other vans, such as the <ORGANIZATION> Chevrolet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Astro </ORGANIZATION>, there is a pillar in the center which reduces rear viewing. Also changed from the earliest <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> minivan models are the engine options. The base engine for a Voyager has gone from a 2.2-liter four-cylinder powerplant to a 2.5-liter four-cylinder. Also offered is an optional 3-liter V-6, which boosts performance but decreases fuel economy. The test model had the V-6 paired with a three-speed automatic transmission. The V-6 certainly is an improvement over the standard four-cylinder, but I had to put in 15.3 gallons of gasoline after 263 combined city-highway miles. That worked out to around 17-18 miles per gallon. There were nice touches throughout. Because the engine and components take up much of the small hood and under-the-dash space, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> tucked the drawer-ike, locking glovebox under the passenger-side bucket seat. There was a center console on the ceiling that included map lights for driver and front-seat passenger, sunglasses storage and a spot for garage door transmitter. In the rear, there were two compartments for storing small items and spots to rest two cups. Outdoor enthusiasts who tow boats, campers, etc. will note that <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s front-drive configuration does limit towing capacity, however. With the standard 2.5-liter four-cylinder, the Voyager can handle up to 2,000 lbs. with the V-6 and Class II frame-mounted trailer hitch, it can take 2,750 lbs. In contrast, many rear-drive vans can handle bigger loads. Consumer Reports says 1984-86 <ORGANIZATION> Plymouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voyagers </ORGANIZATION> have ranked average or above average in reports of trouble.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Job </PERSON>, former executive business editor of The <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, writes biweekly automobile reviews for The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. She has covered the automobile industry for six years.
</TEXT>
