<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   09-08 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0585</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> has filed civil insider trading, fraud and stock manipulation charges against the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>, the head of its junk bond trading unit, and others. In the 184-page civil complaint, filed Wednesday at <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> said it would seek to have the defendants surrender profits made on the affected stock trades and pay a penalty of three times the profits. The firm and <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> reiterated previous statements denying any wrongdoing. The suit capped months of speculation that the government had assembled an extensive case against the firm as a result of the investigation into Wall Street abuses spawned by the <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON> insider trading scandal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> rookie analyst, <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sui-Kuan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, 24, has pleaded guilty to the first criminal charges stemming from what the government has called the second-largest insider trading case in Wall Street history. In another insider trading development on Wednesday, a fired <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> stockbroker, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Dillon </PERSON>, 34, pleaded guilty to fraud after admitting he traded securities based on advance knowledge of the contents of a stock-touting column in undistributed copies of Business Week magazine.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's commercial banks enjoyed their most profitable six months on record through June this year, despite continuing losses in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, the government reports. Commercial banks earned $ 10.5 billion in the first and second quarters this year, topping the $ 9.7 billion in net income for the second and third quarters of 1985. Also on Wednesday, a private panel of bankers, economists and labor leaders released a report urging that banks and debtor nations renegotiate existing loans rather than seek new ones to help ease the $ 1 trillion Third World debt problem.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has come up with a paperwork way to reduce the reported <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit by about $ 3 billion before the election, but officials denied that the accounting change was politically motivated. Commerce Under Secretary <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortner </PERSON> said Wednesday the change made more sense economically. The new procedures will change how merchandise imports get counted each month.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Shareholders of <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> overwhelmingly have approved Chairman <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>'s proposal to buy their shares and take the nation's seventh-largest airline private. But opposition to the move mounted Wednesday among <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> employees as the 3,300-member pilots union sued <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> in <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to block the privatization. Airline industry analysts estimate the <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> bid puts a value of around $ 40 a share, or $ 304.8 million, on the <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> shares that <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> does n't already own. <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> stock closed at $ 36.75 on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, up 37 -LCB- cents a share.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
