 Here is a summary of Wednesday's developments in the federal investigation of insider trading: _ The <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> filed civil insider trading and stock manipulation charges against the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>, the head of its junk bond trading unit <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>'s director of enforcement, said the allegations involved 18 series of transactions, including 16 involving <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>, the former stock speculator now in prison. _ <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sui-Kuan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a former junior analyst at the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, pleaded guilty in to the first criminal charges stemming from what the government has called Wall Street's second largest insider trading case <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> is said to have stolen market-sensitive information about pending takeovers and sold it to a Taiwanese businessman, <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, who the government alleges used the information to make at least $ 19 million on stock trades. _ <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Dillon </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> stockbroker, pleaded guilty to a second count of wire fraud after admitting he had traded stock based on the contents of an investment column in undistributed copies of Business Week magazine <PERSON> Dillon </PERSON> was the first person to face criminal charges as a result of the Business Week investigation.
