<HEAD>Former Morgan Stanley Junior Analyst Pleads Guilty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A key figure in what federal prosecutors call Wall Street's second-biggest insider trading scandal ever has pleaded guilty to criminal charges amid indications that others may be charged. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sui-Kuan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a 24-year-old former junior analyst with the venerable firm <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, pleaded guilty Wednesday in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> to the first criminal charges leveled in the case. <PERSON> Wang </PERSON>, who was free on a $ 250,000 personal recognizance bond, also agreed to plead guilty to a criminal charge in connection with a separate, previously undisclosed insider trading scheme he allegedly undertook when he first began working for <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> in June 1986. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Rudolph </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON>, who outlined the charges at a news conference, said <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> was cooperating with the government and that the investigation was continuing, an indication that others may be charged. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON> set sentencing for Oct. 19. <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> faces a maximum punishment of 15 years in prison and $ 750,000 in fines for the three fraud counts against him. The charges were the first criminal counts made in the scandal first dicslosed in late June in a civil complaint by the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. Prosecutors charged <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> with using his position at <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> to steal market-sensitive information about pending takeovers and other confidential matters in which the firm played a role. The government alleged <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> peddled the information starting in June 1987 to a Taiwanese businessman, <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, who allegedly used it to make at least $ 19 million in profitable stock trades in more than 14 companies and shared about $ 200,000 with <PERSON> Wang </PERSON>. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> was named as an unindicted co-conspirator, but <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> declined to explain why <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> was not charged. Federal officials said <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, also known by his Chinese name <PERSON> Chwan </PERSON> <PERSON> Hong </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, was in <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> has frozen the U.S.-based assets of both men and requested return of the $ 19 million plus triple penalties for a total of $ 76 million. That amount makes the case the second-biggest insider trading scheme next to the record $ 100 million in illicit profits and penalties surrendered by now-imprisoned Wall Street speculator <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON> nearly two years ago. The <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> case is considered significant not only because of the amount of money involved, but because the alleged abuses came at the height of a public uproar over Wall Street greed and corruption highlighted by the <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON> scandal. It suggested that insider trading remains a deep-rooted problem. <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> said <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> cooperated in the government's investigation and faces no criminal liability, but also indicated the firm should have done more to detect <PERSON> Wang </PERSON>'s activities, which the former analyst allegedly undertook during much of his internship <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Roche </PERSON> did not return telephone calls for comment on Wednesday. The firm fired <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> after the scandal first was disclosed and has stated it believed adequate precautions were taken. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>'s lawyer <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Morton </PERSON>, at the <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> firm <ORGANIZATION> Buchanan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ingersoll </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PC </ORGANIZATION>, said in a telephone interview that the criminal charges against <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> were news to him. He declined to comment on any aspect of the case or his client. <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> said the separate, previously undisclosed insider trading scheme involving <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> included an unidentified person living in the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> area, where <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> grew up. <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> said the person was not a Wang relative or engaged in the financial business, but declined to elaborate. In that scheme, <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> said, <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> fed market-sensitive tips about developments in at least five companies to the other individual, who used the information to make profitable trades and rewarded <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> with about $ 4,000. <PERSON> Wang </PERSON>, who attended the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Champaign-Urbana </LOCATION>, won a coveted internship at <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> before he graduated and was only days short of completing it when the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> brought its civil complaint.
