<HEAD>Court Order Stalls Lucky-American Stores Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The proposed $ 2.5 billion merger of <ORGANIZATION> Lucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has been blocked temporarily by a federal judge as <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s attorney general fought the plan he said would bring higher food prices to the state. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenyon </PERSON>, who issued a temporary restraining order Wednesday, said he believed the acquisition of Lucky supermarkets by <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION>, parent of the <ORGANIZATION> Alpha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beta </ORGANIZATION>'s supermarket chain, threatens `` serious irreversible harm'' to Californians <PERSON> Kenyon </PERSON> scheduled a hearing Sept. 16 on whether to grant a preliminary injunction sought by <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON>. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON>, who sued to prevent the merger, says that transaction coupled with the recent acquisition of Oakland-based <ORGANIZATION> Safeway </ORGANIZATION> stores by El Monte-based <ORGANIZATION> Vons </ORGANIZATION> spells higher prices for consumers. He said a survey he commissioned indicated the two mergers would increase food prices by $ 400 million a year in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> has said the merger of Lucky with <ORGANIZATION> Alpha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beta </ORGANIZATION> would lower consumer food prices by $ 50 million annuallyu. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lillie </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Lucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, in a statement said: `` Judge <PERSON> Kenyon </PERSON>'s ruling was simply designed to maintain the status quo until a hearing on the merits of the case can be heard. We are confident that the court will not want to delay the combination of Alpha Beta and <ORGANIZATION> Lucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> once we have the chance to lay out the facts before him.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> has tentatively approved the <ORGANIZATION> Lucky-Alpha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beta </ORGANIZATION> merger, although it would require American to sell 37 markets to competing chains to maintain competition. Nevertheless, <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON> wants a trial to decide whether the marriage of two supermarket giants is anti-competitive. `` The proposed acquisition threatens serious irreversible harm to the public interest within <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, which outweighs any harm to defendants if the mergers are temporarily restrained,'' <PERSON> Kenyon </PERSON> said in imposing the temporary restraining order. The judge forbade <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> from launching a joint operation with Lucky stores until the matter is resolved in court. The combination would give the <ORGANIZATION> Alpha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beta-Lucky </ORGANIZATION> chain 550 stores. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON>, who has threatened similar court action in the Vons-Safeway merger, said talks are progressing on reaching an out-of-court settlement of that dispute. He praised <PERSON> Kenyon </PERSON>'s decision on the Lucky-Alpha Beta proposal <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> did not immediately react to the developments. A Lucky spokeswoman referred calls to American. In his ruling, <PERSON> Kenyon </PERSON> ordered <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> to refrain from selling, transferring or closing any retail grocery stores in the areas where both <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> and Lucky presently compete. The judge said <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> must continue the operations of Alpha Beta independently of Lucky stores and must refrain from supplying either with the assets of the other or exchanging confidential business information. The restraining order barred American and Lucky from entering into contracts which might hinder any future divestiture of the Lucky assets. <PERSON> Kenyon </PERSON> also prohibited any change in the management team of Lucky or of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> operation. American's attorney, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothman </PERSON>, had told the judge that the Lucky management team was poised to take control of the joint operation. In the earlier completed merger, <ORGANIZATION> Vons </ORGANIZATION> acquired 172 Safeway stores which are in the process of being converted to <ORGANIZATION> Vons </ORGANIZATION> operations. <ORGANIZATION> Vons </ORGANIZATION> will have 350 stores. American, which recently moved its headquarters from <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Irvine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, is one of the nation's largest supermarket companies. Its holdings include Acme markets on the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Skaggs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alpha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beta </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Alpha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Beta </ORGANIZATION> and Buttery in the West and the 27-state <LOCATION> Osco </LOCATION> drug chain.
