<HEAD>Survey: Biotech Sales Rising, But Most Companies Still
Unprofitable</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Biotechnology companies' product sales rose 25 percent last year, but three-quarters of the companies lost money, according to a survey by <ORGANIZATION> Arthur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Fifty-eight percent of the companies had lower profits this year than last year, apparently because they were spending heavily for the future, while 74 percent lost money, according to the survey released Wednesday by the accounting and consulting firm The companies' research and development spending rose 32 percent, outpacing revenue growth, the survey said. Biotechnology companies are having a hard time raising money through stock offerings, especially since the stock market crash, and therefore are spending the cash accumulated through past financings in hopes of getting products to market and earning the respect of investors, the firm stated. `` They expect _ and need _ to impress Wall Street again,'' the firm said. `` The strategy is obviously risky.'' <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> concluded that the biotechnology industry is beginning to fulfill its promise, although `` the road remains rough in some sectors.'' `` The general public was thinking in terms of writing the obituary to this industry,'' said <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Burrill </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Arthur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION>'s high technology group. A survey that drew responses from executives at 291 companies found that on average they expected 32 percent of the companies to be acquired within five years and 46 percent to be acquired within 10 years. The executives' estimate may be too high, <PERSON> Burrill </PERSON> said. He said the biotech companies' close linkages with larger companies would limit their attractiveness to other big companies that might want to acquire them.
