<HEAD>NJ Pizza Company Chief To Scout Sites For Restaurants In Soviet
Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MORAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If he ca n't teach them capitalism, at least he'll give them heartburn. The man who brought American pizza to the Soviets via a roving concession truck in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> now says he is working to establish the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s first full-fledged pizza parlor. <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Piancone </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Roma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Piscataway </LOCATION>, said Wednesday he plans to meet next week with Soviet officials in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and inspect several potential sites for a pizza restaurant in the capital and two other cities. `` We are going to be looking at several locations in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Riga </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tula </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Piancone </PERSON>. <PERSON> Piancone </PERSON> and his partner, Ukranian-born entrepreneur <PERSON> Shelley </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zeiger </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Moorestown </LOCATION>, entered a joint venture with Soviet officials last year to bring the company's <ORGANIZATION> Astro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pizza </ORGANIZATION> mobile concession truck to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. The truck began selling slices of the American fast food to tourists and Soviet customers in April. `` Our sales so far have been extremely lucrative,'' he said. `` This is just the next logical step.'' To date the truck has been using ingredients purchased in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> because Soviet tomatoes, cheese and other products were not readily available. <PERSON> Piancone </PERSON> said his trip will include a meeting with <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> officials to discuss the feasibility of using products grown locally. The mobile pizza parlor made a splash in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> when it began operating on a snowy day in April, selling more than 1,200 slices of the cheese-and-tomato pie in just three hours. Since opening, <PERSON> Piancone </PERSON> said the truck has operated three days a week for tourists, accepting only Western currency, and three days a week for local customers, selling slices for 1.25 rubles, roughly just more than $ 2 a slice. The truck does not make rounds on the seventh day. <PERSON> Piancone </PERSON> said it was always his intention, and the intention of his Soviet partners _ who by law own 51 percent of the enterprise _ to open permanent restaurants around the country. He said the company is concerned that competitors may take the initiative away if <ORGANIZATION> Astro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pizza </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> does n't move quickly. <ORGANIZATION> PepsiCo </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and Pizza Hut Restaurants earlier this year announced their intention to open two restaurants in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Piancone </PERSON> said neither has opened yet. But he said a <PERSON> Baskin </PERSON> <PERSON> Robbins </PERSON> ice cream parlor opened in the lobby of a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> hotel. The ice cream parlor does not accept Soviet currency, which is not readily convertible on currency markets. `` I think the people in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> kind of resent that approach,'' <PERSON> Piancone </PERSON> said.
