<DATELINE>BOURNEMOUTH, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The creation of a single European market in 1992 wo n't undermine the national identities of the 12 member countries of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, an <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> chief said Thursday. <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Delors </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, promised delegates to the <ORGANIZATION> Trades </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' annual conference that workers' rights will be respected when the community eliminates national trade barriers in four years. `` You, dear friends, will remain British. We will all maintain our individual ways of life and our valued traditions,'' <PERSON> Delors </PERSON> told the delegates, who represent 9.1 million workers from 85 unions affiliated with the national labor federation. <PERSON> Delors </PERSON> said the post-1992 single market of 320 million Europeans will create new job opportunities and better living standards for workers. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Delors </PERSON> said, the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> will spend 40 billion pounds, or about $ 70 billion, in economically deprived regions of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> to reverse industrial decline, fight long-term unemployment, develop rural areas and provide jobs. The community's member countries are <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britian </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>.
