<HEAD>Sanctions Opponents Seeking To Halt Proposed Measures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Republican members of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> made clear today that it will be difficult, if not impossible, to build bipartisan support for legislation imposing new and stern economic sanctions against white-dominated <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. And <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials suggested that any action on the measure to institute an almost-total trade embargo on <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and to pull out most <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> investment might disrupt delicate ongoing negotiations involving independence for <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> and the withdrawal of cuban troops from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. The committee set a vote for Wednesday on the measure as statements from individual <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> members indicated the legislation will not enjoy the wide bipartisan support given the milder sanctions bill that became law over President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s veto two years ago. Sen. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lugar </PERSON>, R-Ind., a key supporter of sanctions legislation in 1986, called the present bill `` untimely'' and told the committee, `` There are occasions when legislation is not always helpful. `` At this moment, to go into a total disruption of our business in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> does not benefit anyone,'' <PERSON> Lugar </PERSON> said, adding that the measure would remove any leverage the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has to bring pressure on <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> to end its apartheid system of forced racial separation. Sen. <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kassebaum </PERSON>, R-Kan., agreed, saying she does not believe that comprehensive sanctions will end apartheid `` We simply create havoc,'' she said. `` To strike out alone with a package that requires complete disinvestment and a total trade embargo does not behoove us at this time.'' Speaking for the bill, Sen. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON>, D-Calif., said it is designed to `` increase the costs of maintaining apartheid. `` If we fail to focus on <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> we will, in essence, allow the South African regime to declare victory ...,'' <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON> said. `` We have a moral obligation to continue to press for freedom for all South Africans.'' Sen. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.C. </LOCATION>, is reportedly ready to submit up to 40 amendments designed to dilute the impact of the legislation during its examination by the Foreign Relations panel. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is considered highly likely to veto new sanctions legislation if the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> follows the lead of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and approves a bill blocking most trade with <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and requiring practically a complete withdrawal of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> business investment. <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, D-Ill., another backer of the harsh sanctions measure, said on Wednesday they believed the measure could be brought to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor for a vote in the waning days of this year's session, despite a tight legislative schedule But both said it would be difficult to pass the bill in the absence of significant Republican support. They said opponents could make it difficult even to get it past the Foreign Relations Committee. Even if both of those hurdles were cleared, there would not be enough support to override a veto, they said. But any action, even passage by the committee, would `` send a signal to the government of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> that pressure is rising'' against apartheid, <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> said. `` I know of no other way to send that signal, other than sanctions,'' he said. <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> said his recent five-day trip to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> convinced him that it is time for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to adopt the most punishing economic sanctions to date as a signal to <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> that its apartheid policies of racial repression must be abandoned. `` Blacks are living in despair and hopelessness, and whites are living in fear,'' <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> told a news conference. `` And the greater the fear, the more there is repression.'' `` <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> is drifting toward massive violence and the community of nations has to signal to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> that peaceful change has got to come about,'' he said. The House bill, passed on Aug. 11 by a vote of 244-132, has become a focal point of election-year politics. Many Democrats would like to force the issue in order to portray Republicans who oppose it as weak on civil and human rights. Opponents contend stronger sanctions would impose further economic hardship on black South Africans and strengthen the government's resolve to resist pressure for change from outside. A more limited sanctions measure was enacted two years ago over <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s veto, an action made possible only with significant <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> support in both chambers.
