<HEAD>Hyatt Makes $397 Million Offer for Ramada Inc.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Hyatt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> offered Thursday to buy rival hotelier <ORGANIZATION> Ramada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> for an estimated $ 397 million. Ramada officials were noncommittal after Hyatt announced its bid, but investors reacted enthusiastically to the offer, bidding <ORGANIZATION> Ramada </ORGANIZATION> stock up $ 2.12 -LCB- a share to $ 9.75 in <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trading. Hyatt chief <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Pritzker </PERSON> made the offer in a letter to <ORGANIZATION> Ramada </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Snell </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hyatt </PERSON> spokeswoman <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Rugen </PERSON> said. `` We have believed for some time that an affiliation of our companies would be mutually beneficial,'' <PERSON> Pritzker </PERSON>'s letter said. Spokesman <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said the Ramada board would meet to discuss the offer before the close of business next Friday, the deadline set by <PERSON> Pritzker </PERSON> in his letter. <PERSON> Pritzker </PERSON>'s letter said the proposal would expire `` if you have not indicated a sincere desire on or before'' the deadline set. `` Should you choose not to commence a dialogue with us or should market conditions warrant, we may take unilateral action to increase our stake in the company or to dispose of any or all or any part thereof.'' Neither Cole nor Ms. <PERSON> Rugen </PERSON> could comment beyond company statements when asked whether the offer was considered hostile. Hyatt offered to pay $ 10 for each of <ORGANIZATION> Ramada </ORGANIZATION>'s 39.7 million outstanding shares, or a total of $ 397 million. <ORGANIZATION> HCC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Hyatt </LOCATION> affiliate, already holds 2.8 million shares, or 7.2 percent, of Ramada stock, Ms. <PERSON> Rugen </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said it has been known for some time that the <PERSON> Pritzker </PERSON> family, which founded the closely-held Hyatt, has been interested in <LOCATION> Ramada </LOCATION>. `` The last conversation before this offer -LRB- was in -RRB- March of this year,'' he said. At that time, Ramada officials told Hyatt officials they were not interested, <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Pritzker </PERSON>'s letter said <PERSON> Hyatt </PERSON> had cash on hand for the transaction. `` Our proposal to acquire all of the equity of the company is not conditioned upon financing and we have available sufficient funds to consummate the transactions contemplated hereby,'' <PERSON> Pritzker </PERSON> wrote. Ramada companies operate 800 hotels, mostly moderately priced, in 40 countries. They include <ORGANIZATION> Ramada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inns </ORGANIZATION>, Rodeway motels and the upscale Ramada Rennaissance hotels. <PERSON> Ramada </PERSON> also owns 135 restaurants in the <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Callender </PERSON>'s chain, <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said. In 1987, the company had revenue of $ 226.6 million from hotels, $ 406.8 million from gaming operations and $ 113.1 million from restaurants, <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said. Hyatt subsidiaries, all owned by the <PERSON> Pritzker </PERSON> family, operate 144 luxury hotels in many major cities worldwide, Ms. <PERSON> Rugen </PERSON> said. Hyatt in 1985 announced plans to build 40 hotels by late 1990 in areas outside the the major cities which had formed the base of its business. Ms. <PERSON> Rugen </PERSON> would not comment Thursday when asked if the proposed acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> Ramada </ORGANIZATION> was linked to that plan.
