to UPDATE with Senate passage. Picks up 7th graf pvs, The
railroad...
^By CLIFF EDWARDS</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> commuters were spared a morning `` rush-hour nightmare'' when the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> railway and one of its unions agreed Thurssday to delay a likely strike. `` Both sides agree that this is a step that is in the best interest of commuters,'' 41,000 of whom use C & amp; NW commuter trains serving the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> area, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Carle </PERSON>, a spokesman for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Sen <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, D-Ill. The 2,600 members of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> at the railroad had planned to walk off their jobs at 12:01 a.m. CDT Friday, when a 36-day cooling-off period ends and the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> had planned to lay off 1,150 of the 2,300 union brakemen in its 10-state freight operation. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> late Thursday gave unanimous approval to <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>'s bill implementing recommendations of a presidential emergency board, which in July called for trimming 689 brakemen. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> appointed the panel in April to study the labor dispute and seek a solution. <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> predicted the measure would sail through the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on Friday and win quick approval from <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. He said the bill could be passed by late morning and signed an hour or so later by the president. Under the Railway Labor act, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the president have specific authority to settle railroad disputes that threaten national commerce. The railroad and the union have been battling for more than a year over the size of train crews on C & amp; NW freight trains. The company contends the brakemen's jobs are obsolete and that trains can be run with a two - or three-man crew _ an engineer, a conductor and, in some cases, a fireman The union contends the brakemen _ two on each train's crew _ are necessary to maintain railroad safety. The two sides have failed to reach a compromise and earlier this week had implemented strike plans. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Markgraf </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> UTU </ORGANIZATION> general chairman, said he opposes federal intervention, but that the union would honor the settlement if it is approved by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The railroad expects <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to push through the legislation, said <ORGANIZATION> C </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; NW spokesman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Foote </PERSON>, but he noted that management personnel had been deployed throughout the freight system and about 8,000 replacement workers had been recalled. C & amp; NW commuters also were bracing for a walkout _ the third threatened this year. The <ORGANIZATION> UTU </ORGANIZATION> struck C & amp; NW for about four hours Aug. 4, after an earlier cooling-off period imposed by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. During that period, the special presidential board proposed a compromise to end the impasse. Both sides then rejected the proposal _ the one now going before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> _ setting the stage for the August strike. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, however, ended that strike quickly by imposing a second cooling-off period.
