<HEAD>Champion International Reopens Five Mills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Champion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has reopened five <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> mills after workers ratified a three-year contract. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Elder </PERSON>, a Champion spokesman, said Tuesday the wood products company would bring back its 2,400 union workers on a staggered basis. The mills had been idle since the workers struck June 6. Elder predicted it would be late this week or early next week before all mills were running normally again. The strike by the <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Woodworkers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> ended last week when workers approved a new contract calling for a $ 1,400 signing bonus this year, a 3 percent wage increase for 1989 and a 4 percent raise in 1990. The Champion settlement left about 2,700 timber workers still on strike in the <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION>, spokesmen for the two unions said Wednesday. Some 5,200 <ORGANIZATION> IWA </ORGANIZATION> members and 800 <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> members are voting this week on a proposed settlement with <ORGANIZATION> Weyerhaeuser </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. Results and contract details are to be announced Sept. 13.
